commit_message:
Cache the ARP entries in L3 Agent for DVR

There seems to be a timing issue between the
ARP entries that arrive from the server to
the agent and the internal qr-device getting
created by the agent.
So those unsuccessful arp entries are dropped.

This patch makes sure that the early ARP entries
are cached in the agent and then utilized when
the internal device is up.

Conflicts:
        neutron/agent/l3/dvr_router.py
        neutron/tests/unit/agent/l3/test_agent.py
        neutron/tests/unit/agent/l3/test_dvr_local_router.py

Closes-Bug: #1501086
Change-Id: I9ec5412f14808de73e8dd86e3d51593946d312a0
(cherry picked from commit d9fb3a66b4aead65fac2df08a5f34538e7af4d7b)

commit_message:
Kill conntrackd state on HA routers FIP disassociation

Legacy routers kill conntrackd states on FIP disassociation,
so that traffic to FIPs that have been disassociated is properly
dropped. This is not the case with HA routers, and this patch
changes that.

Change-Id: Ic962c518ce33a4936d0f1655d60d308c5e776a9b
Closes-Bug: #1505700
(cherry picked from commit e0eeadc97ee094d6dfa5f4139c1c4aa871b514d5)

commit_message:
api tests: don't hide exception when creating load balancer

When the test fails, it's not clear what happened. We should not hide
details about it from those who will review test failure logs.

Change-Id: If68b4f93820085c4d9154d6b2aae8529f9c69da8
Related-Bug: #1505932
(cherry picked from commit 88d27442c24c3b730e02b6e658d697f8eba781d9)

commit_message:
Fix punctuation in doc strings.

I was reading through some of the doc strings in federation/utils.py and
noticed a forward-slash where there should have been a period. This commit
replaces it with a period.

Change-Id: Ia26e894b76e29bb9e78ddaea83efaa3a96175a6c

commit_message:
Fix UnexpectedError exceptions to use debug_message_format

The point of UnexpectedError is to hide the real error from the
client so that extra information won't be sent to an attacker.
This only happens when the debug_message_format is set rather
than message_format. Several UnexpectedError implementations
were setting message_format rather than debug_message_format so
this has been corrected.

Change-Id: I77efba7437b56936041c26c35e9c68760806455e

commit_message:
Fix exceptions to use correct titles

The exception title is used as the text in the HTTP response line.
HTTP has specific titles for response codes, so we can't just
override the title to whatever we want as this violates HTTP.

Change-Id: I8f1363c7b7f2549004b1d98af4410e23f8cb71fe

commit_message:
Add theme fix for browsable source code

This adds a fix to ensure that the published docs have the correct
link to the browsable source code as implemented in
https://review.openstack.org/236091

It also includes an exclusion of the doc directory from the pep8
check as the documentation conf.py requires the lengthy line.

It also updates the dev-requirements for the docs jobs to ensure
that the requirements are in line with upstream.

Change-Id: I52b5ede12667cf454d99a053e20eba4461b8ee75

commit_message:
Migrate playbooks to use 'become'

Ansible is scheduled to remove the 'sudo' module
and replace it with 'become'. Switch to using this
now since it is already supported in 1.9.

Closes-Bug: #1504535

Change-Id: Ie63816e36a95c86d54fea5f50325522b41597047

commit_message:
begin process to update to astara

This is the first step in converting the repo for Astara. This includes
changes to console scripts, new default users and packaging hooks.

Change-Id: If8e383e86cf867b8167f22b4411edf167d6cbd9a
Partially-Implements: blueprint convert-to-astara

commit_message:
Enable debug logs for octavia in neutron gate

When something fails in gate, we need to have all logs collected for
analysis.

Change-Id: I1c1bf79aea3f161907d81abb66363a4aa7d2af12
Related-Bug: #1505932
(cherry picked from commit 2a8701920a559b034320e94c5aecf09e4c7c2b78)

commit_message:
avoid duplicate text in ISCSIError message

The ISCSIError class defines a class-level message attribute with
value: "Error starting iSCSI target". This attribute is further
processed in RESTError.__init__ method, the ISCSIError super-class, to
create an Exception message concatenating self.message with provided
details argument.  However, the ISCISError.__init__ method provides a
details attribute prefixed with the same text to the super(ISCSIError,
self).__init__ method.  As a result, the text appears twice:
"ISCSIError: Error starting iSCSI target: Error starting iSCSI target:
ISCSI daemon didn't initialize. Failed with exit code 107. stdout: .
stderr: tgtadm: failed to send request hdr to tgt daemon, Transport
endpoint is not connected"

The patch purpose is to remove the details prefix to avoid duplicate
text in the exception text while honouring ISCSIError.message.

Change-Id: I9e1434ae17da5112527a841ac069ed2285566cca

commit_message:
Fix broken filtering by tags in v3

The code rearranges lines to enable filtering by tags.

Example:
/withprops/v1.0/drafts?tag=cicici&tag=hyhyhy

Closed-Bug: 1489126

Change-Id: I8f5b004c884aaf4d3ad97b3f8a98012b6706c425

commit_message:
Modify simulator.py tool

Introduce mechanism of generating real life messages to the tool
using the information gathered during Rally testing. This change
allows to generate messages of the specfic length due to the
distribution observed on real environment.

messages_length.txt file contains lengths of string JSON objects
that were later sent through the MQ layer during deployment and
deletion of 50 VMs.

simulator.py was modified to use this data as a baseline to generate
random string messages of the required length with the needed
probability.

Change-Id: Iae21f90b5ca202bf0e83f1149baef8b42c64eb55

commit_message:
Clarify what gerrit repositories can target neutron-specs

It wasn't made clear by the existing documentation that we only want
neutron, neutron-fwaas, neutron-lbaas, and neutron-vpnaas repositories
to target specs at neutron-specs. This makes it 100% crystal clear.

Change-Id: I5b87faa31d71676f1674fd7370535ae6d895b43f
Signed-off-by: Kyle Mestery <mestery@mestery.com>

commit_message:
Add REST API endpoint for the third page view

This commit adds a rest api endpoint for the third page view. It takes
in a build_name from the url and returns a time series dict of all
the test runs which ran as part of a run which were that build_name.
The start date, stop date, and resolution of the time series is
adjustable with url params.

The third page will use this with the key being a project and the
value being whatever project the page is being generated for.

Change-Id: Ic3a74954015dd6b3bcc8eab4c8854e60906e7a85

commit_message:
Removing package patch versions from APT pinning

APT package pinning to not existing version can cause accidental
package removal, especially when running apt dist-upgrade.
Not existing version refer to missing packages inside the APT
repository/mirror.

This fix does only pin lxc and libvirt-bin to specific major and
minor versions allowing package variations lxc-1.0.7-0ubuntu0.1
to 1.0.7-0ubuntu0.9 for example by inserting a wildcard.

Change-Id: I930699aa8328374730b3bcc0ccda23f5ff86b106
Closes-Bug: #1483877

commit_message:
New command to install Tempest's plugins in rally verify

Install Tempest's plugins from physical path.
E.g.
  $ rally verify install_plugin --path ~/my-plugin
Blueprint: https://blueprints.launchpad.net/rally/+spec/install-tempest-plugins

Change-Id: Ibf5dbfe16924ff6e9cf7ed8f174deb0bd4261afa

commit_message:
New command to install Tempest's plugins in rally verify

Install Tempest's plugins from physical path.
E.g.
  $ rally verify install_plugin --path ~/my-plugin

Change-Id: I57c31cfab7489bb35242b3381e5f85c3a0871197
Blueprint: https://blueprints.launchpad.net/rally/+spec/install-tempest-plugins

commit_message:
Fix response of Compute Virtual Interface API

Nova v2.1 base virtual interface API does not include "net_id"
attribute in response. It was added in microversion 2.12.

This commit fix the above mentioned API response code for v2.1 base version.
Also removing VIF extension entry from extension list and add Note about
difference between v2 and v2.1 API.

Closes-Bug: 1506294

Change-Id: I483aad0bd64a2560a650c4f7a4a8965daa39349c

commit_message:
Use noop octavia driver for minimal job too

Seems like without the driver being set, octavia attempts to run the
load balancer in an amphora, and it fails for some reason to transit the
object into ACTIVE state.
Also remove the amphora boot related gate settings.

Change-Id: I1eb239ff18fb7ad77d0839f725029a703bd14982
Closes-Bug: #1505932
(cherry picked from commit 6de135a973bd8225dcabd799ae4a06f32ee0c744)

commit_message:
Remove check for service_type in openwrt mgmt driver

Currently check for 'service_type' in openwrt fails,
because of the change of 'service_type' from VNF level to
VDU level. This patch will remove the check for 'service_type'
in OpenWRT mgmt driver.

Closes-Bug: #1506111
Change-Id: I1de206779841ca63e1f95cc9f5bd58496566acfe

commit_message:
Add Linux-HA resource agent

The OpenStack HA guide [1][2] describes how to configure the Linux
clustering components Corosync and Pacemaker to run OpenStack services
as active/passive HA processes.  The repository for the necessary
scripts, known as resource agents, is no longer maintained, and the
suggestion is to keep the scripts closer to the projects themselves.
So, we can keep the Manila resource agent in the Manila source tree
under contrib/pacemaker.

The Manila resource agent was modeled after the one for Cinder, plus
a few fixes needed to make it work with Devstack.  A separate commit
to the OpenStack HA Guide will add a section covering Manila.

[1] http://docs.openstack.org/high-availability-guide/content/ch_preface.html
[2] https://github.com/openstack/ha-guide

Change-Id: I8524dfd49a7c5bc2ce6b2e54b38ca74033f893a5
Implements: blueprint publish-manila-ha-resource-agent

[{'account_id': 3, 'date': '2013-07-06 16:06:39.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 1: Doesn't seem to work

Build failed

- https://jenkins.openstack.org/job/gate-quantum-merge/604/consoleFull : SUCCESS
- https://jenkins.openstack.org/job/gate-quantum-pep8/482/consoleFull : SUCCESS
- https://jenkins.openstack.org/job/gate-quantum-python26/252/testReport : SUCCESS
- https://jenkins.openstack.org/job/gate-quantum-python27/252/testReport : FAILURE
"}, {'account_id': 261, 'date': '2013-07-06 16:06:39.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 1:

While I agree to all Gary's comments, I think that the scope of this patch was merely to allow a specific plugin to log on a distinct file.

The patch itself is very simple and straightforward, and I don't feel like we should reject it on the grounds that we want to do something better. 
Note: the log path for the agent does not appear to be hardcoded.

As soon as the agent-logging blueprint (https://blueprints.launchpad.net/quantum/+spec/agent-logging) will be implemented, we can get rid of this code.

So, I'd say reject this change if somebody (Maybe Armando himself) can commit to agent-logging for F-3, otherwise we can just accept it."}, {'account_id': 261, 'date': '2013-07-06 16:06:39.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 1:

Juliano, 
It's all yours!"}, {'account_id': 748, 'date': '2013-07-06 16:06:39.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 1:

I cannot guarantee that I could fix logging across the board for F3, though I would love to. That said I am happy to abandon this patch if you guys think it only adds noise.'}, {'account_id': 748, 'date': '2013-07-06 16:06:39.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 1:

Ok, so I had a look around and it seems that the ovs agent relies on its own way common config (available in plugins/openvswitch/common/config.py)

I wouldn't want to pull a dependency on quantum-common (quantum/common/config.py) as I don't have enough experience with the project to know whether this split in configuration is by design or by accident. 

In the former case, it seems that logging configuration would need to be duplicated; in the latter, it seems there's too much work to refactor the configuration agent-side, and I don't feel this should be done in the context of this patch.

Please advise, many thanks."}, {'account_id': 748, 'date': '2013-07-06 16:06:39.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 1:

jenkins failed while installing pip deps'}, {'account_id': 748, 'date': '2013-07-06 16:06:39.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 1:

Of course! it would be better to log to syslog, exposing logging levels, formatters via config file etc, but that was not my intention; I just wanted simple logging, without the hassle of redirecting standard output. We can always augment later.'}, {'account_id': 748, 'date': '2013-07-06 16:06:39.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 1:

good point, I hadn't noticed...I'll have a look. 
Thanks."}, {'account_id': 3, 'date': '2013-07-06 16:06:39.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 2: Works for me

Starting gate jobs.'}, {'account_id': 3, 'date': '2013-07-06 16:06:39.000000000', 'content': 'Change has been successfully merged into the git repository.'}, {'account_id': 3, 'date': '2013-07-06 16:06:39.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 2: Verified

Build successful

- https://jenkins.openstack.org/job/gate-quantum-merge/631/consoleFull : SUCCESS
- https://jenkins.openstack.org/job/gate-quantum-pep8/509/consoleFull : SUCCESS
- https://jenkins.openstack.org/job/gate-quantum-python26/279/testReport : SUCCESS
- https://jenkins.openstack.org/job/gate-quantum-python27/279/testReport : SUCCESS
'}, {'account_id': 261, 'date': '2013-07-06 16:06:39.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 2: Looks good to me (core reviewer); Approved

'}, {'account_id': 748, 'date': '2013-07-06 16:06:39.000000000', 'content': 'Uploaded patch set 2.'}, {'account_id': 1653, 'date': '2013-07-06 16:06:39.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 1: I would prefer that you didn't merge this

Hi,
Great idea to fix the logging! I think that three things need to be done:
1. If we are going to address logging for one agent then I think that it should be done across the board - that is, support for the linuxbridge and ryu agents too
2. I think that you should leverage the common configuration code (currently used by the agents) to configure the various logging configurations. In your code you hard coded the logging path.
3. I think that we should have common code for the agents and plugins. Logging is a classic example. I suggest that you write a proposal to the mailing list to get people comments and views.
Thanks for taking this task. It will certainly things.
Thanks
Gary"}, {'account_id': 1653, 'date': '2013-07-06 16:06:39.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 1: No score

First and foremost my bad regarding the "hard coded" name. Sorry.
As far as I am concerned you can continue with this. It would be nicer if this was in a greater scope but I guess that we can address that in the future.'}, {'account_id': 1653, 'date': '2013-07-06 16:06:39.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 2: Looks good to me (core reviewer)

It works! Thanks for the change in the logging.'}, {'account_id': 2350, 'date': '2013-07-06 16:06:39.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 1: I would prefer that you didn't merge this

Why not to use the quantum common methods for logging? 

https://github.com/openstack/quantum/blob/master/quantum/common/config.py#L52

Maybe a configuration to use syslog or a logfile should be a good way."}, {'account_id': 2350, 'date': '2013-07-06 16:06:39.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 1:

I think this plugin was created before quantum common, but we need a second opinion on what to do here.

A core dev will help here soon, but an email on the mailing list would be good :).'}, {'account_id': 4381, 'date': '2013-07-06 16:06:39.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 1:

I can do it for F-3, I tried change the "Assignee" but wasn't allowed. Is it possible to someone assign it to me?'}, {'account_id': 4381, 'date': '2013-07-06 16:06:39.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 1:

Armando sorry, I sent the message before read you comment. If you'd to get it go on :D. I will need a common agent log to use with the generic-firewall-agent. 

Thanks"}, {'account_id': 4381, 'date': '2013-07-06 16:06:39.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 1:

It wouldn't be better log it to syslog instead of create a new log file? Using the syslog you don't have to think about rotate and things left inside the system."}, {'account_id': 7787, 'date': '2015-10-22 05:52:05.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 2:

(1 comment)'}, {'account_id': 748, 'date': '2015-10-22 17:54:26.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 2:

(1 comment)'}]

commit_message:
Change required version of ImcSdk to 0.7.2

There was a bug discovered in ImcSdk 0.7.1 with the SSL handshake that
caused problems when running Ironic for longer periods of time, this
patch changes the required version to the latest version of the ImcSdk
which contains a fix for this issue.

Change-Id: I7665e953b73ed83d5fb5d8adfbed5b3647e5ed48
Closes-Bug: #1508849

commit_message:
Remove requests to example.com during unit testing

When unit tests are launched some of these tests are attempting
to access http://example.com. This is not convenient in case
if somebody doesn't have an access to internet.
In order to fix this
- some tests in test_script_utils were deleted
  cause they tested urllib instead of glance
- Some responses were replaced with FakeHTTPResponses
- Some requests were redirected to local http server

commit_message:
Add ability for octavia to allocate vip

Adds a configuration option (defaults to False) to allow octavia to be
responsible for allocating the VIP.  If this is the case, then the driver will
then update the neutron-lbaas load balancer database with the vip information.

This satisfies a few use cases where a single port created by neutron lbaas
on behalf of the user is too restrictive for more complex vip allocation needs
that Octavia does and will support.

Closes-Bug: #1463594
Change-Id: Idd52d5d8325f1447aadcdf9c687ce010a6488cf6

Ok, I think this is on the right track, but I think it would be easier to understand the logic if it were reversed: have the helper methods return True if they're done doing what they need to do and False if they need to do more work. So, in general, the helpers could do something like:

  if not i_need_do_do_things:
      return True
  try:
      do_the_needful()
  except Exception as exc:
      if is_immutable(exc):
          return False
      raise
  else:
      return True

Then, in the check_create_complete, you do something like:

   return helper1() and helper2() and helperN()

I think this makes the code a lot easier to understand."}, {'account_id': 3, 'date': '2015-10-09 17:57:11.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 3: Verified+1

commit_message:
Do not pass rich objects in Cloud LoadBalancer create

Remove passing of rich objects in the Rackspace::Cloud::LoadBalancer
resource during create to make the resource compatible with the
convergence Heat engine.

Change-Id: Iac3e41d06d31c1aaea5f066a91aae611d3e851af
Closes-Bug: #1486463

commit_message:
Do not pass rich objects in Cloud LoadBalancer update

Remove passing of rich objects in the Rackspace::Cloud::LoadBalancer
resource during update to make the resource compatible with the
convergence Heat engine.

Change-Id: I14a7af419b081e7126e75e8332cb1fd7dace5dd9
Partial-Bug: #1486463

revisions:
[{'created': '2015-05-18 12:22:07.000000000', 'message': 'HyperV: Add named pipe handler

This patch adds a named pipe handler performing IO operations.

This handler will spawn workers running in native threads. It can
accept queues used for interacting with the named pipe.

If a log file path is provided, this will be used for logging the
named pipe output. Log rotation will be performed in order to limit
the total log size to 1 MB.

Partially-implements: blueprint hyperv-serial-ports

Change-Id: I20ba3640abe3613aa096a593e51a04f4f3fad286

commit_message:
HyperV: Add named pipe handler

This patch adds a named pipe handler performing IO operations.

This handler will spawn workers running in native threads. It can
accept queues used for interacting with the named pipe.

If a log file path is provided, this will be used for logging the
named pipe output. Log rotation will be performed in order to limit
the total log size to 1 MB.

Partially-implements: blueprint hyperv-serial-ports

Change-Id: I20ba3640abe3613aa096a593e51a04f4f3fad286

subject: HyperV: Add IOQueue class used for named pipe IO operations

commit_message:
HyperV: Add IOQueue class used for named pipe IO operations

This patch introduces a queue wrapper that relies on a connected
event in order to cancel pending operations in case a consumer is
disconnected.

This also helps us stop IO workers almost immediately.

Partially-implements: blueprint hyperv-serial-ports

Change-Id: I2bcc5687b3eb14b8be10fe53d6281ae506163285

subject: HyperV: Add IOUtils class for asynchronous IO operations

[{'created': '2015-05-18 12:22:07.000000000', 'message': 'HyperV: Add IOUtils class for asynchronous IO operations

Hyper-V exposes VM serial console ports via named pipes. At the
moment, those are consumed only in read-only mode.

This blueprint proposes to add interactive serial console access
support. This implies reading and writing to named pipes at the
same time.

This change introduces a class used for asyncronous IO operations.

R/W operations are performed asynchronuously, having a callback
that will be executed when the operation completed or a certain
event is signaled. This requires the thread to be in an alertable
wait state.

As those operations will be executed in separate native threads,
we cannot use logging. Also, locks must be used with caution.

Partially-implements: blueprint hyperv-serial-ports

Change-Id: I34caae59c5cd8eeeb2b276d6c42e35d13700f6c9

commit_message:
HyperV: Add IOUtils class for asynchronous IO operations

Hyper-V exposes VM serial console ports via named pipes. At the
moment, those are consumed only in read-only mode.

This blueprint proposes to add interactive serial console access
support. This implies reading and writing to named pipes at the
same time.

This change introduces a class used for asyncronous IO operations.

R/W operations are performed asynchronuously, having a callback
that will be executed when the operation completed or a certain
event is signaled. This requires the thread to be in an alertable
wait state.

As those operations will be executed in separate native threads,
we cannot use logging. Also, locks must be used with caution.

Partially-implements: blueprint hyperv-serial-ports

Change-Id: I34caae59c5cd8eeeb2b276d6c42e35d13700f6c9

[{'created': '2015-10-19 16:18:22.000000000', 'message': 'Added CORS support to Heat

This adds the CORS support middleware to Heat, allowing a deployer
to optionally configure rules under which a javascript client may
break the single-origin policy and access the API directly.

For heat, the paste.ini method of deploying the middleware was
chosen, because it needs to be able to annotate responses created
by keystonemiddleware. If the middleware were explicitly included
as in the previous patch, keystone would reject the request before
the cross-domain headers could be annotated, resulting in an
error response that was unreadable by the user agent.

OpenStack CrossProject Spec:
   http://specs.openstack.org/openstack/openstack-specs/specs/cors-support.html
Oslo_Middleware Docs:
   http://docs.openstack.org/developer/oslo.middleware/cors.html
OpenStack Cloud Admin Guide:
   http://docs.openstack.org/admin-guide-cloud/cross_project_cors.html docimpact

Change-Id: I185f0d9f85617dd2f482cac4994ccc0a4cb6cf16

commit_message:
Added CORS support to Heat

This adds the CORS support middleware to Heat, allowing a deployer
to optionally configure rules under which a javascript client may
break the single-origin policy and access the API directly.

For heat, the paste.ini method of deploying the middleware was
chosen, because it needs to be able to annotate responses created
by keystonemiddleware. If the middleware were explicitly included
as in the previous patch, keystone would reject the request before
the cross-domain headers could be annotated, resulting in an
error response that was unreadable by the user agent.

OpenStack CrossProject Spec:
   http://specs.openstack.org/openstack/openstack-specs/specs/cors-support.html
Oslo_Middleware Docs:
   http://docs.openstack.org/developer/oslo.middleware/cors.html
OpenStack Cloud Admin Guide:
   http://docs.openstack.org/admin-guide-cloud/cross_project_cors.html docimpact

Change-Id: I185f0d9f85617dd2f482cac4994ccc0a4cb6cf16

commit_message:
Use yaml.safe_load instead of yaml.load

We currently use yaml.load to read a user-written config file. This can
lead to malicious code execution, so we should use yaml.safe_load
instead.

Found using bandit.

Change-Id: I27792f0435bc3cb9b9d31846d07a8d47a1e7679d

commit_message:
[Contrib Guide] Backport section to RST & final edits

This patch:
- translates the below wiki page to RST:
  https://wiki.openstack.org/wiki/Documentation/HowTo#Git_commit_messages_and_backports
- creates a new folder called Additional Git workflow and moves the file
  cherry-pick.rst to this folder;
- replaces '_' with '-' in some file names for consistency;
- changes the files order in the index.html file;
- updates text for the Abstract section in Introduction.

Change-Id: Icd66e1af93a12f1c3fc827ce228001dced9aa065
Implements: blueprint docs-contributor-guide

Brad Klein, Does this change look OK to you. It looks pretty safe. I just don't want to breadj anything in production.

The idea is that the Agent will look for meta data with the key "scale_group". If it doesn't exist, it will not be supplied as a dimension. If it is available, it will be supplied as a dimension.'}, {'account_id': 2419, 'date': '2015-10-15 14:23:01.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 5: Code-Review-1

(1 comment)'}, {'account_id': 2419, 'date': '2015-10-15 14:23:41.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 5:

Brad Klein, Never mind my prior request. I think this code needs more work. Do you agree?'}, {'account_id': 8126, 'date': '2015-10-15 14:58:00.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 5: Code-Review-1

Agreed Roland, the metadata call needs to be handled similar to the way the flavor cache is build/retrieved.  Otherwise we'll be hammering nova again.."}, {'account_id': 12809, 'date': '2015-10-16 03:20:43.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 5:

(1 comment)'}, {'account_id': 8126, 'date': '2015-10-16 14:40:44.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 5: Code-Review+1

Thanks for the explanation Sripadwallabda, I'm OK with this change..."}, {'account_id': 12443, 'date': '2015-10-16 18:17:55.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 5: Code-Review-1

Is scale_group a common metadata key?  I can find no reference to it in the openstack docs.  If this is something specific to one site or customer and therefore NOT a common key, I'd hate for everyone else to take the performance hit.

Two questions:
1) Would it be better to use the entire instance metadata dict as a dimension?  That would capture scale_group if it exists, or whatever metadata other clients are using.
2) Does "nt.servers.get(instance.id).metadata" potentially contain different data from from "instance.metadata"?  The latter would not require another Nova API call.'}, {'account_id': 2419, 'date': '2015-10-20 00:58:18.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 5:

There are a few fixes that I think shoudl be made before this code is merged:

1. The query for meta data should only occur if enabled. In other words, the query should not just be automatically done all the time, and if no meta data is available, just continue on and be ignored. The check should be explicitly enabled. The problem is that these types of queries are extremely expensive.

2. The results of the query should be cached similar to the other results, such as flavors and tenant ID, that are cached. The reason is the same as above. These types of queries are extremely expensive.

3. You should probably make the solution more general and have the operator be able to specify the meta data they would like to send as dimensions. Scale group is not a well-defined and industry standard name. So, I think the preference is to generalize the solution so that the operator can specify any meta data that they would like to send as a dimension. The other problem is that is "scale_group" does appear in the meta data, it isn't always that the operator wants that data to be treated as a dimension.'}, {'account_id': 12809, 'date': '2015-10-20 06:46:16.000000000', 'content': 'Uploaded patch set 6.'}, {'account_id': 3, 'date': '2015-10-20 06:49:46.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 6: Verified+1

- gate-monasca-agent-python27 http://logs.openstack.org/30/232630/6/check/gate-monasca-agent-python27/d3c39e1/ : SUCCESS in 1m 04s'}, {'account_id': 12809, 'date': '2015-10-20 06:50:21.000000000', 'content': 'Uploaded patch set 7.'}, {'account_id': 3, 'date': '2015-10-20 06:53:11.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 7: Verified+1

Build succeeded (check pipeline).

- gate-monasca-agent-pep8 http://logs.openstack.org/30/232630/7/check/gate-monasca-agent-pep8/03950a2/ : SUCCESS in 42s
- gate-monasca-agent-python27 http://logs.openstack.org/30/232630/7/check/gate-monasca-agent-python27/a86a8a5/ : SUCCESS in 52s'}, {'account_id': 12809, 'date': '2015-10-20 06:56:14.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 7:

1. The query for meta data occurs if enabled in config file (libvirt.yaml) otherwise metadata query is not made.
2. The results of the metadata query are cached similar to the other results, such as flavors and tenant ID etc. No extra nova client call is made.
3. The solution is more generic now operator can specify the which metadata tags he needs to be sent as dimensions 
4. Also updated example libvirt.yaml file to add metadata section.'}, {'account_id': 10487, 'date': '2015-10-20 06:58:30.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 7: Code-Review+1

Roland, David and Craig: Now the changes are fine i believe, it addresses all the review comments. Thanks Sripad.'}, {'account_id': 12443, 'date': '2015-10-20 16:46:30.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 7: Code-Review+1

I like the new approach.  Nicely done.'}, {'account_id': 2419, 'date': '2015-10-20 17:44:14.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 7: Code-Review+1

Hi Sripa, This code looks good to me! Thanks for making all the changes. I have no further concerns.'}, {'account_id': 8126, 'date': '2015-10-20 18:15:31.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 7: Code-Review+1

awesome!'}, {'account_id': 11809, 'date': '2015-10-20 19:09:23.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 7:

I like the new approach. It is much cleaner. It only needs one more piece, the ability to set metadata from the detection plugin called by monasca-setup.

In monasca_setup/detection/plugins/libvirt.py you need to add some code to evaluate self.args. In build_config(), I used:

        if self.args and 'metadata' in self.args and self.args['metadata']:
            init_config['metadata'] = ast.literal_eval(self.args['metadata'])

This allowed me set the metadata using:

/opt/monasca/bin/monasca-setup \
    -d libvirt \
    -a "metadata=['scale_group']"

I'm not saying that code is absolutely correct, it is just something I tried'}, {'account_id': 10487, 'date': '2015-10-21 03:14:41.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 7:

Craig, I believe we could push that as follow up patch to enable the config in setup, as this patch makes required changes for enabling the scaling. kindly let me know otherwise. thanks.'}, {'account_id': 2419, 'date': '2015-10-22 17:10:53.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 7: Code-Review+2 Workflow+1'}, {'account_id': 3, 'date': '2015-10-22 17:10:58.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 7: -Verified

commit_message:
Add scale_group dimension to libvirt plug-in

Adds additional dimension scale_group to the
metrics reported by libvirt monasca agent plugin,
to help heat auto-scaling.
Change-Id: I280438c6f9e4ea297c268e83f535d422d0370a53
Closes-Bug: #1504042
Co-Authored-By: Kanagaraj Manickam <kanagaraj.manickam@hp.com>

commit_message:
Fix SA warning of empty sequence during tests

While running tests, a warning for image_locations.id
being an empty sequence is shown. This is due to an
empty list of location id passed in the IN clause of
query. Added a check to not add the in clause if the
list is empty.

Closes-Bug: #1358904
Change-Id: I3747c60fc6528b72256979d6b1c59ccb8d52e9e2

commit_message:
Fix application name in constants_spec.js

The unit test suite was failing due to a test in constants_spec.js
that expected the application name (as defined in constants.js) to be
"Example Application". This commit changes the expected value in the
test to "StackViz".

Change-Id: Ia7b97fdaae3560a27d944c81a9a245feafde3252

commit_message:
Set ip_nonlocal_bind in namespace if it exists

Somewhere in the 3.19 kernel timeframe ip_nonlocal_bind was
changed to be a per-namespace attribute. To be backwards
compatible we need to try that first, then fall-back to
setting the one in the root namespace if it fails.

Closes-Bug: #1507078
Change-Id: I018e800bc8d4e85d067aaae865c9b04bf030c980
(cherry picked from commit 24acc41b9314729a0fbbc88b1f8cb19a331a3dc7)

[{'created': '2015-10-08 05:56:27.000000000', 'message': "XenServer: the cron job shouldn't print debug text into stderr

one cron job attempts to print debug text into stderr; so the file
of /root/dead.letter gets created and its size grows continuously.
It could eventually threaten dom0 disk space. Maybe there are two
solutions: one is to redirect the output to a specific log file;
and rotate log files in the script. And the other one is simply
to redirect the output /dev/null. By considering the function of
this cron job and the printed contents are straight and simple,
this patch set goes with the later solution.

Change-Id: I4875e5e3837e6f0249e314c6c5f408c79145c6c1
Closes-Bug: 1503966
"}]
commit_message:
XenServer: the cron job shouldn't print debug text into stderr

one cron job attempts to print debug text into stderr; so the file
of /root/dead.letter gets created and its size grows continuously.
It could eventually threaten dom0 disk space. Maybe there are two
solutions: one is to redirect the output to a specific log file;
and rotate log files in the script. And the other one is simply
to redirect the output /dev/null. By considering the function of
this cron job and the printed contents are straight and simple,
this patch set goes with the later solution.

Change-Id: I4875e5e3837e6f0249e314c6c5f408c79145c6c1
Closes-Bug: 1503966

update history import tools for liberty

Ignore git tags that appear to be part of a series other than liberty.

revisions:
[{'created': '2015-09-23 12:10:00.000000000', 'message': 'Remove quotes from subshell call in bash script

Always no quotes for $() statement.

We don't need quotes to hold blanks in result:
 # i=$(echo 1 2 3)
 # echo $i
 1 2 3
 #

These quotes can make something wrong in some case:
 # i=$(echo '!')
 #
 # i="$(echo '!')"
 -bash: !: event not found
 #

No real problem for current code, only to use a better code style.

Change-Id: I3c87987d3b992c8363ef236a04ae6e35c1315535
Signed-off-by: Zhao Lei <zhaolei@cn.fujitsu.com>
'}]
commit_message:
Remove quotes from subshell call in bash script

Always no quotes for $() statement.

We don't need quotes to hold blanks in result:
 # i=$(echo 1 2 3)
 # echo $i
 1 2 3
 #

These quotes can make something wrong in some case:
 # i=$(echo '!')
 #
 # i="$(echo '!')"
 -bash: !: event not found
 #

No real problem for current code, only to use a better code style.

Change-Id: I3c87987d3b992c8363ef236a04ae6e35c1315535
Signed-off-by: Zhao Lei <zhaolei@cn.fujitsu.com>

commit_message:
handle routers without an external gateway in list_router_interfaces

list_router_interfaces would fail if called on a router with no external
gateway:

    File "/home/lars/.ansible/tmp/ansible-tmp-1445525437.55-149961620412652/os_router", line 343, in main
      ports = cloud.list_router_interfaces(router, 'internal')
    File "/usr/lib/python2.7/site-packages/shade/__init__.py", line 1922, in list_router_interfaces
      ext_fixed = router['external_gateway_info']['external_fixed_ips']
    TypeError: 'NoneType' object has no attribute '__getitem__'

This commit defaults `ext_fixed` to an empty list if there is no external gateway.

Change-Id: Idbcd5f005ebef47e11377e83a60d2adea7c3380b

commit_message:
Lookup parent network for floating range by CIDR

Floating range was always considered as subrange within Public network of default node group.
Now, lookup of parent network for floating range by CIDR is implemented.
So, floating range may match any Public network of a cluster.

Co-Authored-By: Aleksei Kasatkin <akasatkin@mirantis.com>

Change-Id: I7d8b0c1db0835aec9e035177e076e40f4e793902
Closes-Bug: #1502829

commit_message:
Use nginx proxy for packages before netconfig

When we use multirack topology then right after provisioning all
nodes from non-default node-group have default route set to their
rack router IP. So in case of isolated admin network (when local
package mirrors and/or Internet are not accessible via admin net)
such nodes won't be able to download and install any packages
until we configure all the interfaces (management, public, etc).
And network configuration itself requires some OVS packages.
In order to solve this issue we setup nginx proxy on Fuel master
node and configure Apt to use it. We remove it after netconfig
task.

Integration tests disabled since they won't pass until we merge
Ida30b5de9f730821ae969032019adf409cfa82ca and upload ISO with it
to CI slave nodes.
Fuel-CI: disable

Change-Id: I7d729a1ca6c602b033e697c26ca7ce3f429849dc
Closes-bug: #1497378

commit_message:
Setup nginx proxy for packages

Run nginx proxy on Fuel master node on port 2080. This proxy is
used by nodes so they could download and install packages before
network is fully configured and mirrors are directly accessible
from the nodes.

DocImpact

Change-Id: Ida30b5de9f730821ae969032019adf409cfa82ca
Partial-bug: #1497378

commit_message:
[doc] Improve devstack plugin installation docs

Improve layout, add links to devstack, mention cfapi service.
Replace github references with git.openstack.org references.
Also removes unnecessary enable_service instructions in cfapi docs, to
be consistent with plugin documentation

Change-Id: I0235db31fe8dd80ada1a627a9d02e61d1236488f
Related-Bug: #1506232

commit_message:
If-None-Match header removed from container

If-None-Match support was added to Create container and Create
Object on assuming the context of commit message title. Above
parameter has been deleted from container Api-docs as per
Developers suggestion.

Change-Id: I87bd2126a1f4b8db86d8908470539d59de9419ef
Partial-bug: #1400794

commit_message:
Shared File Systems API: removed 'local' network_type

A valid value of the network_type is VLAN, VXLAN, GRE, or flat.
The 'local' value was removed.

(df) Updated links in share files to relative links.

Change-Id: I7725f246dfd0ba452817f25a24c4ad760aaf0cdc
Closes-Bug: #1507616

commit_message:
Remove config-drive and server-usage section in v2.1 compute API doc

v2.1 compute API doc now contains servers section. The current
config-drive and server-usage section can be removed as they
are already included in the servers section.

(df) Add response parameters for list server details and
show server details calls.
(df) Consolidated the server actions into one section and added
response parameter descriptions.
(df) Updated the links at the top of the Compute v2.1 page
to be in alphabetical order, and to put all extensions at end of the page.
This is what triggered refactoring of the server actions. Also, some of
the page-level links were incorrect. I fixed those.

Co-Authored-By: Diane Fleming <diflemin@cisco.com>

Change-Id: I0cbcd2c219c68b3331d5221679412813e5be507c
Closes-Bug: #1506699

commit_message:
Fixed name for test run for Tempest results

We are going to use new name pattern for test runs,
need to use 'kilo' prefix for reports.

Change-Id: I5a91546ab6c77bc53267bb2a12dafc2bf1bb5a50
Closes-Bug: #1506779

commit_message:
Add document about default config filename

The default config file path and name is hard-coded but not documented.
So people don't know the default file path and name without reading the
code. So this commit adds the document as a NOTE.

Change-Id: I44598ebcafefa63e717cbecb3353f03e9344eff0

At the moment in "Add the Image service" we link to the trunk version of
the config reference which redirects to the Liberty config reference at
the moment. We should directly link the Libery config reference to not
use the Mitaka config reference with the Liberty install guide in the
future.

Change-Id: I4fbcf8791ecde078a8ce9dd7a46947c6dd7ac5c0
'}]
commit_message:
[install] link to the Liberty config reference

At the moment in "Add the Image service" we link to the trunk version of
the config reference which redirects to the Liberty config reference at
the moment. We should directly link the Libery config reference to not
use the Mitaka config reference with the Liberty install guide in the
future.

Change-Id: I4fbcf8791ecde078a8ce9dd7a46947c6dd7ac5c0

commit_message:
Move rally.osclients.Clients to plugin base

Current implementation is not flexible. In near future(I suppose it will
be done in next patch) an ability of setting clients versions will be added.
Also, the same situation with service types.

Each client have each own validation(nova supports microversions, designate
accepts only str values of version, zaqar accepts only int values and etc).
Moving from method for client initialization to classes(Plugin-based) allows
to implement unique validations when it required.

Also, this patch unify usage of designateclient: use
designateclient.client.Client entry-point instead of hardcoded versioned
module.

Change-Id: Iefe2edf2be97708fe761624711a62cdcd109ccc3

commit_message:
Fix date format passed to dbapi

There was some rest endpoint method which wasn't parsing start and stop
date format before calling dbapi method. It was causing warning because
these fields were not in same format as run_at db field. This change
implement the _parse_datetimes call properly where was missing.

It was necessary update the timestamp variable on tests because the
dbapi call is made regardless minutes and seconds.

Change-Id: I3bb4cf4d1efebad0b81926a400dc91c8b647b4fd

commit_message:
Adding metrics and CSS styling to HTML formatter

This commit adds a metrics summary to the top of the HTML report.
It also adds some CSS styling to the report to make it a bit more
visually appealing.

revisions:
[{'created': '2015-09-08 09:20:17.000000000', 'message': "DVR: notify specific agent when create/update port

Now in DVR scenario, if we create a VM in one subnet
which has added to a DVR router, neutron-server will
firstly schedule this router to all related l3 agents,
then send 'routers_updated' RPC message to these l3
agents, in large scale, there is a serious performance
problem.
This patch makes two changes in DVR:
1. if a l3 agent in one compute node has not bind to a DVR
   router, when we create a VM in this compute node, we just
   schedule the router for this l3 agent, and just send
   'routers_updated' RPC message to this l3 agents.
2. if a l3 agent in one compute node has bind to a DVR router,
   when we create a VM in this compute node, we just need to send
   'routers_updated' RPC message to this l3 agents.

Change-Id: Idc7f3b9537d12a232c02d48a18f010506bb0b52e
Closes-bug: #1486795

commit_message:
DVR: notify specific agent when create/update port

Now in DVR scenario, if we create a VM in one subnet
which has added to a DVR router, neutron-server will
firstly schedule this router to all related l3 agents,
then send 'routers_updated' RPC message to these l3
agents. In large scale, there is a serious performance
problem.
This patch makes two changes in DVR:
1. if a l3 agent in one compute node has unbound to
   the existing DVR router, when we create first VM in this
   compute node, we just need to schedule the router for this
   l3 agent, and send 'routers_updated' RPC message to this l3 agent.
2. if a l3 agent in one compute node has bind to a existing DVR router,
   when we create a VM in this compute node, we will not send
   'routers_updated' RPC message to any l3 agent, just send add_arp_entry
   message.

Change-Id: Idc7f3b9537d12a232c02d48a18f010506bb0b52e
Closes-bug: #1486795

So notify the specific agent rather than notify all agents.
This will save some RPC resources.

Notify specific agent when create or update port

The L3 agent was determined when create or update port.
So notify the specific agent rather than notify all agents.
This will save some RPC resources.

commit_message:
This adds baseline filtering to bandit

You can now provide bandit with a previous output report, in JSON
format. If given we will use this report to filter results. Results
will only be reported when the number of issues detected in a file
is not the same as the number that was detected in the baseline run.
If there is a discrepancy then all issues from the file will be
reported as we cant reliably determin the spoecific new issues
found.

Change-Id: Ia24ee665892ae59d7904776b9ff2637364ead213

subject: Fix default config filename
messages:
[{'account_id': 5689, 'date': '2015-10-22 14:59:13.000000000', 'content': 'Uploaded patch set 1.'}, {'account_id': 5196, 'date': '2015-10-22 15:03:33.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 1: Code-Review-1

So this is a bit confusing, but the default config filename here is not actually referring to the config file located in etc/ of the repo. (that is strictly for local dev and testing) but a fallback location for the api to look at if a config file isn't specified on the CLI.

In the case of running this under mod_wsgi, like we do for the production server, there isn't a way to pass in values to sys.argv. So we write the config file to /etc/openstack-health.conf and the api server will pick it up automatically.

Changing this will break the production server because the config file won't be in the right location anymore."}, {'account_id': 5689, 'date': '2015-10-22 15:09:17.000000000', 'content': 'Abandoned

@Matthew, Thanks for your review.
I see. I think we should have a document for the default config name.'}]

commit_message:
[Reports] Reduce histogram charts weight to make report faster

This patch removes histogram view `One Half', which seems to be
rarely used but holds a lot of data for JavaScript.

For example, there is a listing of how much data is generated for
JavaScript by MainHistogram, on dummy scenario with 50000 iterations:

   Square Root Choice - 224 points
   Sturges Formula - 17 points
   Rice Rule - 74 points
   One Half - 25000 points!!!

Removing this view causes HTML report to work much more faster.
In some cases (like given above) this actually revives the report.

Change-Id: I6f51e72b93084f57eaf8cc5a107a0dd103824944

commit_message:
Use noop octavia driver for minimal job too

Seems like without the driver being set, octavia attempts to run the
load balancer in an amphora, and it fails for some reason to transit the
object into ACTIVE state.
Also remove the amphora boot related gate settings.

Change-Id: I1eb239ff18fb7ad77d0839f725029a703bd14982
Closes-Bug: #1505932

commit_message:
Resolve repeated ports for ssl frontends (nova vnc and swift proxy)

Nova vnc and swift proxy were listening on the same port if SSL is
enabled in the load balancer

Change-Id: Ibf4aa118d6c8e94f8f2a68bf270d5445ebda7593

Sort projects by percentages of failure.

The projects now will be displayed ordered by the percentage of

commit_message:
Add a tests view

This commit adds a tests view to the dashboard, it has a bar graph
for all tests showing the failure rate and then a table listing the
per test stats for each test. This is a good starting point for
diving down into per test details.

Co-Authored-By: Glauco Oliveira <gvinici@thoughtworks.com>
Co-Authored-By: Caio Carrara <ccarrara@thoughtworks.com>
Change-Id: I56938734775c603cf5bac4f082d6dfae290dfbd0

commit_message:
Add functional_creds.conf to .gitignore

This patch adds two files to .gitignore.
*  `functional_creds.conf` is used for functional test
* `functional-tests.log` is generated by functional test

Change-Id: Ie21e8e20078770746117a8976444d9a72fd45d55
Closes-Bug: #1508797

commit_message:
Make openstack module tests work under puppet 4

This change updates the rsyslog default for the custom config option to
be '' rather than undef so that the correct file is used for the client
and service configurations under puppet 4. Additionally this change
fixes the parameter check for rabbit_hosts for the openstack module so
that it passes.

Change-Id: I128abd4cc27297d76db8f6d05e583cfbeae8abc7
Closes-Bug: #1507614

commit_message:
Create Rakefile to execute lint and spec tasks

This change creates a top level Rakefile that can be used to run all of
the lint, syntax and spec tasks for the modules and files in this
repository.

This is needed to integrate with the openstack-infra puppet syntax and
unit test jobs.

This change disables the unit tests for l23network until they can be
fixed as part of bug 1507742.

Change-Id: I1f637f2f2fd91ce01ba2a92f6ea45499def5333d
Related-Bug: #1507751
Related-Bug: #1507742

commit_message:
The exception type is wrong and makes the except block not work

According to the context, it should be KeyError here to catch.
AttributeError will not happen here. More details could be found
in the bug report.

Change-Id: Id6351172703ac492e86475f75bf1be03f4e4e8a3
Closes-bug: #1506934
(cherry picked from commit 9d6584120003f50782461677d1b783bd07131444)

commit_message:
Add coverage reports to tests

This change adds simplecov to show the coverage of the noop test files
and also includes the output from the rspec-puppet reports into the
coverage/ folder.

The simplecov report is a report that is merged together based on the
entire noop test run. It will show where we have astute.yaml gaps for
our given noop spec tests.

The rspec-puppet reports are named based on the astute.yaml file that
was used to generate each report.

Change-Id: I9dda550c960fb2742f1f0862305e144a3fb1d9d6
Closes-Bug: #1506557

commit_message:
Prevent parallel execution of some dockerctl subcommands

The commit causes dockerctl to fail if another instance of script
is already running a container-changing function, i.e. export, start,
destroy, backup and restore. A global variable is used to allow
high-level functions like backup correctly re-use the lock for start
or destroy functions.

Change-Id: I5dc99adeacb901f11ea576674b4fdc64868b8784
Closes-bug: 1386578

commit_message:
Move CN in OpenStack public endpoint certificate to SAN

As recommended by RFC2818, RDN and email part of CN moved to SAN in
certificate for public OpenStack endpoints in case of self-signing.

Change-Id: Iaf8a949bf35e599842fe3a8a045f9140e442a380
Closes-Bug: #1507806

commit_message:
Fix ssh dir mocks

Prior to this change if the root user's home directory was not /root,
the tests would fail due to improper mocking of the file system. This
change updates the order in which the directories are created and
ensures that we use the environment's user directory rather than
assuming /root.

Change-Id: I558e3b9971346a741d6409b3a8f00005e99eae3e
Closes-Bug: #1508124

[{'account_id': 18898, 'date': '2015-10-20 13:43:24.000000000', 'content': 'Uploaded patch set 1.'}, {'account_id': 10068, 'date': '2015-10-20 13:43:29.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 1:

Thank you for your first contribution to OpenStack.

    Your patch will now be tested automatically by OpenStack testing frameworks
    and once the automatic tests pass, it will be reviewed by other friendly
    developers. They will give you feedback and may require you to refine it.

    People seldom get their patch approved on the first try, so don't be
    concerned if requested to make corrections. Feel free to modify your patch
    and resubmit a new change-set.

    Patches usually take 3 to 7 days to be reviewed so be patient and be
    available on IRC to ask and answer questions about your work. Also it
    takes generally at least a couple of weeks for cores to get around to
    reviewing code. The more you participate in the community the more
    rewarding it is for you. You may also notice that the more you get to know
    people and get to be known, the faster your patches will be reviewed and
    eventually approved. Get to know others and become known by doing code
    reviews: anybody can do it, and it's a great way to learn the code base.

    Thanks again for supporting OpenStack, we look forward to working with you.

    IRC: https://wiki.openstack.org/wiki/IRC
    Workflow: http://docs.openstack.org/infra/manual/developers.html

Hashmap UI rework

Refactor code to use Horizon's classes
Refactor forms inheritance
Add mixin to order form fields
Populate group list in mappings and thresholds forms

commit_message:
Modify instructions for using delorean to build images

By using DIB_YUM_REPO_CONF to build the images rather
than the delorean-repo element, yum-plugin-priorities does
not get installed in the overcloud images. The NVR of delorean
packages is not perfect, and sometimes there will be older
packages with a newer NVR in the deps repo. Until we can make
delorean always have newer NVR than any released package, we
rely on yum-plugin-priorities to always get the delorean
package over the released package.

Change-Id: I1c314c8532d9541c50836aad3a27222c85c5addf

commit_message:
Use identity_uri instead of auth_uri parameter

auth_uri parameter is not required. Services should only use
identity_uri for inter-cluster operations.

Closes-bug: #1503725
Change-Id: I83850bfe8d422b4ad93e58852524cdb114fcf326

There are alternative ways to handle this. First, there's array-injection notation:

"projectName": ["$stateParams", function($stateParams) {
  // things
}]

Alternatively... don't minify? You get way more bang for your buck if you use mod_gzip and sane HTTP Cache headers on your static resources. Also, minifying usually destroys your ability to debug code at runtime.'}, {'account_id': 17001, 'date': '2015-10-09 15:27:01.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 1:

Well, the use of ngInject here is mainly because the rest of the project is already using it (that is, we're using it in just about every Angular-related file as it is). If we want to investigate removing it for some reason, I feel like that would be best taken care of in a separate patch.

Re: minifying, the current build process includes both minification and gzip. Some back-of-the-envelope testing suggests doing both is significantly better than gzip alone (188KB minified + gzipped vs 1.26MB only gzipped). For debuggability, we do also generate sourcemaps. Unfortunately they aren't helpful in this case because angular is doing crazy things with raw sources, but for just about any sane situation it should be mostly a non-issue."}, {'account_id': 9717, 'date': '2015-10-19 12:06:19.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 1:

See, when I see numbers like that, I question why your project is 1.25 megabytes. If that's all ASCII (Which I hope it's not), that'd be the entirety of War & Peace. In this case, I would say that minification is a cure for a symptom, but the actual cause here is that your codebase is bloated."}, {'account_id': 17001, 'date': '2015-10-19 21:32:28.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 1:

I was a bit surprised too, so I dug a little deeper into the numbers. It turns out that without minification source maps were being included directly in the output bundle (they are normally stripped), which caused quite a bit of inflation. That is to say, my methodology for calculating the numbers in my last comment was flawed.

The correct numbers (with source maps completely disabled) are 1776 KB (438 KB compressed) with no minification versus 644 KB (184 KB compressed). The total size of all resources is 2960 KB unminified (962 KB compressed) versus 1828 KB (709 KB compressed).

Minification still nets a large, positive savings (over 50% a reduction for JS) even with gzip turned on, so I think we still gain a lot by keeping it enabled. Even so, I believe the unminified JS (438 KB compressed) is quite close to other OpenStack Angular projects on its own.'}, {'account_id': 18001, 'date': '2015-10-22 13:51:21.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 1: Code-Review+2 Workflow+1'}, {'account_id': 3, 'date': '2015-10-22 13:51:26.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 1: -Verified

[{'created': '2015-10-08 20:25:10.000000000', 'message': "Add `@ngInject` annotation to project `resolve` config.

During production builds, the minifier modifies variable names,
breaking Angular's automatic dependency injection. The ng-annotate
declaration `@ngInject` was missing from the `resolve` config
for the project route, causing all `/project/` paths to become
inaccessible. This adds the correct annotation to solve the issue.

Change-Id: I06505a8b7f1d74066872d60b5675524845a561fe
"}]
commit_message:
Add `@ngInject` annotation to project `resolve` config.

During production builds, the minifier modifies variable names,
breaking Angular's automatic dependency injection. The ng-annotate
declaration `@ngInject` was missing from the `resolve` config
for the project route, causing all `/project/` paths to become
inaccessible. This adds the correct annotation to solve the issue.

Change-Id: I06505a8b7f1d74066872d60b5675524845a561fe

commit_message:
WIP: Enable boot volume attach

This is an example of how to attach a boot volume. I expect
to change it to make intellegent use of bdms. Other safety
checks based on bdms will be added seperately.

This change allows attachment of a bootable volume to a shutdown
instance if the volume we are trying to attach is the volume used to
boot the instance.

If that check passes then the volume is attached as the root device of
the instance.

Co-Authored-By: Andrea Rosa <andrea.rosa@hp.com>

blueprint detach-boot-volume

Change-Id: I84b76791f4460cad78f4e4db1d58b86f4b3cd77b

This is an example to demonstrate detaching a boot volume. I expect
to change the implementation to make intellegent use of bdms. I
will add other safety checks based on bdms seperately.

It is safe to detach a root disk when a VM is in a stable shutdown
state (vm_state=stopped, power_state=shutdown, task_state=None).
However, currently there is a check in the API that blocks any
attempt to detach a root disk. This patch changes that check so
that it is only applied if the VM is not in that shutdown state.

blueprint detach-boot-volume

Change-Id: I6a781d1648d23f391830d7460a5aaca82f1b5eba
'}]
commit_message:
WIP: Allow boot volume detach when shutdown

This is an example to demonstrate detaching a boot volume. I expect
to change the implementation to make intellegent use of bdms. I
will add other safety checks based on bdms seperately.

It is safe to detach a root disk when a VM is in a stable shutdown
state (vm_state=stopped, power_state=shutdown, task_state=None).
However, currently there is a check in the API that blocks any
attempt to detach a root disk. This patch changes that check so
that it is only applied if the VM is not in that shutdown state.

blueprint detach-boot-volume

Change-Id: I6a781d1648d23f391830d7460a5aaca82f1b5eba

commit_message:
Shared File Systems API: removed info about Quota Classes

Removed the information about quota classes (and the API requests)
in the Shared File Systems API, because the quota classes are not
used in the Shared File Systems service and are not working properly
for the current moment (in Liberty release and all releases earlier).

Change-Id: I9e5ead6af1c09feb27088d7f9898c1959af32e1c
Closes-Bug: #1508882

commit_message:
rabbit: shuffle hosts before building kombu URL

This restores behavior as it was back in the Juno cycle.  This was
changed in a refactor during the Kilo cycle (973301aa) when the kombu
failover_strategy was set to shuffle.  But the failover_strategy only
affects failovers; it does not influence which host receives the
initial connection.

Thus, if multiple hosts are given, the first host will receive all of
the initial connections.  By shuffling the hosts before building the
URL given to kombu, rudimentary load balancing is achieved and
connections are more evenly spread across broker nodes.

Change-Id: Ieecaf5f286f49302db29df9854359ef5d36b7a89
(cherry picked from commit f2beb5eaf158f76cdb8be0ca72965503be423ee2)

commit_message:
Implement new map_merge intrinsic function

Adds a new map_merge function for Mitaka which can be used
to merge maps. Values in latter maps override those in earlier
ones.

Also, creates a new HOT template version for Mitaka which includes
the new map_merge function.

Implements: blueprint map-merge-function
Change-Id: I2bdfc70d04a4fa14cefcf928ea5947fbe7529cf9

[{'created': '2015-10-22 09:40:28.000000000', 'message': "Avoid division operation in shell

When the data returned from 'rabbitmqctl list_queues' grows a lot
and awk sums up all the rows especially for memory calculation it
returns the sum in scientific notation (example from bug
was .15997e+09), later when we want to calculate the memory in
MB instead of bytes, the bash division does not like this string.

We can just avoid the situation by doing the division into MB
in awk itself. Since we don't need the memory in bytes anyway.

Closes-Bug: #1503331
Change-Id: I38d25406b84d0f70ed62101d5fb5ba108bcab8bd
(cherry picked from commit 00a6a016d5235de4cbde26cb40db71119967d3c7)
"}]
commit_message:
Avoid division operation in shell

When the data returned from 'rabbitmqctl list_queues' grows a lot
and awk sums up all the rows especially for memory calculation it
returns the sum in scientific notation (example from bug
was .15997e+09), later when we want to calculate the memory in
MB instead of bytes, the bash division does not like this string.

We can just avoid the situation by doing the division into MB
in awk itself. Since we don't need the memory in bytes anyway.

Closes-Bug: #1503331
Change-Id: I38d25406b84d0f70ed62101d5fb5ba108bcab8bd
(cherry picked from commit 00a6a016d5235de4cbde26cb40db71119967d3c7)

commit_message:
Trivial locking cleanup in test_listener

ListenerSetupMixin.ThreadTracker was reading self._received_msgs
unlocked and sleep/looping until the desired value was reached.
Replaced this pattern with a threading.Condition.

Change-Id: Id4731caee2104bdb231e78e7b460905a0aaf84bf

team.

commit_message:
Import i18n functions directly

As stated in i18n guide it is normal to import i18n functions
(_, _LW..)  directly and we can include i18n functions in
hacking exceptions.
Also there is no need to make exceptions for six moves
because pep8 passes correctly without it.

Change-Id: I9c9aa490f1447bb7ae221809df7bc110c27d1336

commit_message:
Switch cloud-init to absent to fix tests

This change updates the ensure on cloud-init to absent as purged is not
availble on all platforms. This will allow tests to pass cleanly on OSX
or other systems where purged is unavailable.

Change-Id: I43a40b79a022d4f6ed5ddb9479002461416fdea8
Closes-Bug: #1493985

commit_message:
Fix order of arguments in assertEqual

Some tests used incorrect order assertEqual(observed, expected).

The correct order expected by testtools is
assertEqual(expected, observed).

Partial-Bug: #1259292
Change-Id: I86a496e640ceb9402dd2dde2be5281e358ca3592

[{'created': '2015-09-09 07:20:57.000000000', 'message': "Fix MetricWeigher to use MonitorMetricList

The commit e7dab9975bcbe3bb40cb9723b0deaed985b904c changes
'HostState.metrics' to 'objects.MonitorMetricList'. But MetricWeigher
still use the old dictionary of 'host_manager.MetricItem'. This patch
corrects the behavior of MetricWeigher with related tests, and delete
unused MetricItem.

Change-Id: I7c98c2e189318e85a733f0287ef507c7bad36472
Closes-Bug: #1493680

commit_message:
Fix MetricWeigher to use MonitorMetricList

The commit I4dfbea27ce6c3eecc1a8658b1f9dc0feb2298705 changes
'HostState.metrics' to 'objects.MonitorMetricList'. But MetricWeigher
still use the old dictionary of 'host_manager.MetricItem'. This patch
corrects the behavior of MetricWeigher with related tests, and delete
unused MetricItem.

Co-Authored-By: Sylvain Bauza <sbauza@redhat.com>

Change-Id: I7c98c2e189318e85a733f0287ef507c7bad36472
Closes-Bug: #1493680

commit_message:
Add microversion bump exception for scheduler-hint

It seems diffcult to manage schedulers on microversions, so this patch
adds it as an exception.

Change-Id: Ic86e5db39d3b3cd0ba1f182fd82a62cb98fb8075

commit_message:
Pass CONF to logging setup

The function accepts two parameters, the first one being the
current CONF. The second parameter is the product name.

Closes-bug: #1505710

Change-Id: Id53214977f6ed87202c22314f7b864a9d0df8291
(cherry picked from 7668c794f8294b278e7f006d9594fd7653099bac)

commit_message:
Spawn dedicated rpc workers for state reports queue

By default spawn one additional rpc worker to process
state report queue.
State report queue will also be processed by regular
rpc workers, but in case these workers are busy with
processing heavy requests, state reports queue will
automatically be consumed by dedicated rpc workers.

This change applies to ML2 plugin only.
Other plugins should implement start_rpc_state_reports_listener
to enable additional rpc workers.

Change-Id: I5f8df6a478f7c82382049274b34b07109eeafbdb
Closes-Bug: #1505217

commit_message:
Ironic: Call unprovison for nodes in DEPLOYING state

This patch is making the Nova ironic driver to try to unprovision the node
even if it's in DEPLOYING state. Current Ironic will not accept aborting
the deployment when it's in DEPLOYING state but with the retry mechanism
it may work once the state is moved to ACTIVE or DEPLOYWAIT. Prior to
this patch the logic was to not even try to unprovision the node if it's
in DEPLOYING and just go ahead and clean the instance but that behavior
is dangerous and could leave orphan active instances in Ironic. With
this patch at least if the unprovision fails in Ironic we can make sure
that the instance won't be deleted from Nova.

The tests for the destroy() method were refactored to extend testing
destroy() being called with all provision state methods in Ironic
instead of picking certain ones; A helper function was created to avoid
code duplication on the tests.

Partial-Bug: #1477490
Change-Id: I227eac73a9043dc242b7a0908bc27b628b830c3c

An interesting thing is that we forgot to add a rule which denies request body changes without microversion bump.

https://review.openstack.org/#/c/221642/ is for adding it and I am trying to get an exception for scheduler-hint parameter.
So this patch should depend on that.'}, {'account_id': 6167, 'date': '2015-09-09 08:55:42.000000000', 'content': 'Uploaded patch set 5.'}, {'account_id': 6167, 'date': '2015-09-09 09:40:23.000000000', 'content': 'Uploaded patch set 6.'}, {'account_id': 782, 'date': '2015-09-09 10:38:57.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 6: Code-Review+2'}, {'account_id': 782, 'date': '2015-09-09 10:41:07.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 6:

I am OK with this "fix" not having a bump because we are back dating it to all versions.

We could advertise the fix with a version bump, but that seems only borderline useful for these types of bug fixes that apply to older versions.

The user can tell when the hint is accepted, its accepted when they don't get a 400 error when sending it. At least until the point where we relax the validation, at that point, we probably should bump the version.

I could be over thinking this...'}, {'account_id': 3, 'date': '2015-09-09 10:45:41.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 6: Verified+1

commit_message:
Add API schema for different_cell filter

For using the different cell filter, the API parameter different_cell
needs to be passed to the corresponding filter. However v2.1 API
validation denies it because there is not API parameter definition
and it didn't work at all.
This patch adds the API schema.

Change-Id: Ic61b9a18722b7701b09e71f3f3a547ad9e6363c2
Closes-Bug: #1492925

commit_message:
Murano CI Rework: Update common scripts

 - Move common variables and functions into separate files
 - Add support for cross-project dependencies
 - Add cleanup function
 - Add ability to save builded images

Implements: blueprint automated-murano-ci-cleanup
Change-Id: Ib149c336fc6c9dd8105c7fe71cc8654677824a97

commit_message:
Temporary proposal for big tent adoption

This is a draft proposal for making Senlin part of the Big Tent.
Everyone please help review and comment on points we want to make,
wording issues (Qiming is not a native speaker) anyway. Once this is in
shape, we will submit it for TC review.

Change-Id: Ie942e379abacea2c879a4d6b9db9d3a7e6fa5f2b

Resolve repeated ports for ssl frontends

keystone and heat_cfn were listening on the same port if SSL is enabled
inm the load balancer.

commit_message:
Support for Cinder volume replication

Documenting information on how cloud administrators
can adjust the cinder volume driver to enable
volume replication. This feature safeguards environments
from data loss.

Change-Id: I7ba72a14914cb1b0359e532e619ea36dfe1b73e0
Closes-Bug:#1360768

[{'created': '2015-10-20 21:45:01.000000000', 'message': "Fix l2pop regression

Patch https://review.openstack.org/#/c/236970/ introduced an issue
where get_agent_by_host can return a random host (Including L3,
DHCP or metadata agents), not only L2 agents. The caller then
tries to get tunneling_ip, which might not exist on the returned
agent, causing l2pop code to bail out with a WARNING:
'Unable to retrieve the agent ip...'.

The issue was found by manual introspection of the code, and
verified by modifying the l2pop fullstack test to register L3
agents. Both a unit test was added, as well as modifying the
fullstack connectivity test to register L3 agents if l2pop
is enabled.

Change-Id: Ib3072966140b7f6ca954d7847ad9835aa1191998
Closes-Bug: #1508205

commit_message:
Fix l2pop regression

Patch https://review.openstack.org/#/c/236970/ introduced an issue
where get_agent_by_host can return a random host (Including L3,
DHCP or metadata agents), not only L2 agents. The caller then
tries to get tunneling_ip, which might not exist on the returned
agent, causing l2pop code to bail out with a WARNING:
'Unable to retrieve the agent ip...'.

The issue was found by manual introspection of the code, and
verified by modifying the l2pop fullstack test to register L3
agents. Both a unit test was added, as well as modifying the
fullstack connectivity test to register L3 agents if l2pop
is enabled.

The code will now check for agents with a tunneling_ip key
in their configurations dict, which is required for l2pop
to work correctly, essentially a form of duck typing.

Change-Id: Ib3072966140b7f6ca954d7847ad9835aa1191998
Closes-Bug: #1508205

commit_message:
Change section name for AMQP qpid parameters

According to docs for liberty and kilo [1,2] should be
section 'oslo_messaging_qpid' instead of 'DEFAULT'.

[1] http://docs.openstack.org/liberty/config-reference/content/configuring-rpc.html
[2] http://docs.openstack.org/kilo/config-reference/content/configuring-rpc.html

Change-Id: Ic96528a60730a43838e002e639fa7aeb166c2424

IMHO this has gone backwards form patch set 4 - yes, when using the command line, the header keys are title-cased before being passed to put_object. That happens in service.py here:

https://github.com/openstack/python-swiftclient/blob/master/swiftclient/service.py#L259-259

But Connection presents an interface that does not require its headers to be title-cased, and as the original functional test revealed, results are unpredictable when lower case header keys are passed.

Being pragmatic, the patch as it is now does make forwards progress and does fix the issue when using the cli so I am going to add a +A. But the issue with Connection applying headers correctly being case sensitive remains. There is still a bug lurking here.

The commit message is wrong now - the fix is to use 'Content-Type' from custom headers, not to use 'content-type'. So I have fixed that and approved based on the +2's on the previous version."}, {'account_id': 3, 'date': '2015-10-22 09:58:18.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 9: Verified+1

commit_message:
swiftclient content-type header

According to help `swift upload -h` you can add a customized request header 'Content-Type'.
But actually it is ignored (cleared and default is used) if subcommand is upload.

Subcommand post works as expected in help.

Bug fix: Use 'Content-Type' from the customized request headers also if
uploading.

Change-Id: If0d1354b6214b909527341078fe1769aa6587457

commit_message:
Fix unintended assignment of "syslog"

Identifier "syslog" is unintendedly reassigned in _setup_logging_from_conf()
with OSSysLogHandler.
It causes an error in _find_facility() which expects "syslog" as module.
This change fixes the problem.

Change-Id: Icd8486bc008028f6f78f0306d835bf2c4fb9245b
Closes-Bug: #1499620
(cherry picked from commit ff277ae1e9b53b1844ecc220383ab9d39f954881)

Thank you for your first contribution to OpenStack.

    Your patch will now be tested automatically by OpenStack testing frameworks
    and once the automatic tests pass, it will be reviewed by other friendly
    developers. They will give you feedback and may require you to refine it.

    People seldom get their patch approved on the first try, so don't be
    concerned if requested to make corrections. Feel free to modify your patch
    and resubmit a new change-set.

    Patches usually take 3 to 7 days to be reviewed so be patient and be
    available on IRC to ask and answer questions about your work. Also it
    takes generally at least a couple of weeks for cores to get around to
    reviewing code. The more you participate in the community the more
    rewarding it is for you. You may also notice that the more you get to know
    people and get to be known, the faster your patches will be reviewed and
    eventually approved. Get to know others and become known by doing code
    reviews: anybody can do it, and it's a great way to learn the code base.

    Thanks again for supporting OpenStack, we look forward to working with you.

    IRC: https://wiki.openstack.org/wiki/IRC

commit_message:
Replace deprecated LOG.warn with warning

LOG.warn is deprecated. It still used in a few places. This updates
those one to use the non-deprecated LOG.warning instead.

Closes-Bug: 1508442
Change-Id: Id947e4c8ae9894f480192a5ab034c24c25125788

commit_message:
Use Tempest-lib's compute hosts_client

Compute hosts_client has been migrated to
tempest-lib- I59c82bc896d5036d936e6f9cddb3c7b004648dde

Now Tempest-lib provides this client as stable interface so Tempest
should start using this from lib and remove its own copy.
Also remove its unit tests.

This commits makes Tempest to use compute hosts_client
from Tempest-lib.

Change-Id: I5f0846c3fbe2100223f01f9aa9b22c10d75a2468

subject: Use Tempest-lib's compute floating_ips_bulk_client

commit_message:
Use Tempest-lib's compute floating_ips_bulk_client

Compute floating_ips_bulk_client has been migrated to
tempest-lib- I52c0cfcbfd65e3143d608200b6cac07dac006ccc

Now Tempest-lib provides this client as stable interface so Tempest
should start using this from lib and remove its own copy.
Also remove its unit tests.

This commits makes Tempest to use compute floating_ips_bulk_client
from Tempest-lib.

Change-Id: I6d87f6056318b58f83a3be9feef3872ecf694af4

subject: Use Tempest-lib's compute floating_ip_pools_client

commit_message:
Use Tempest-lib's compute floating_ip_pools_client

Compute floating_ip_pools_client has been migrated to
tempest-lib- Iab0f7faca8d23d18061c5b3d13bb8b5e0536025c

Now Tempest-lib provides this client as stable interface so Tempest
should start using this from lib and remove its own copy.
Also remove its unit tests.

This commits makes Tempest to use compute floating_ip_pools_client
from Tempest-lib.

Change-Id: I50b5899e80c77fac6c0757b2d1387c49e0cc4e8c

commit_message:
Use Tempest-lib's compute flavors_client

Compute flavors_client has been migrated to tempest-lib-
I3de529b1e0db298530e54fd2c871d40f29614126

Now Tempest-lib provides this client as stable interface so Tempest
should start using this from lib and remove its own copy.
Also remove other files for this client like response schema, unit tests.

This commits makes Tempest to use compute flavors_client
from Tempest-lib.

Change-Id: I8e5b227bb1bf359c4a194f649dad186eb0574a46

commit_message:
Add backend subrequest tests for staticweb

This is an followup for
https://review.openstack.org/#/c/227204

Above patch changes staticweb to use just make_env instead of
pre authed env. The tests included in this patch assert
"backend requests generated by staticweb *NEVER* include pre
authed information (i.e. authorize_override=True)".

Change-Id: Ifbbc43d3b5ac114bc3d5e4fcab9cacdf9a3f1a5c

[{'created': '2015-09-24 10:10:13.000000000', 'message': 'Do not use pre-authenticated requests in staticweb

staticweb middleware uses make_pre_authed_env, this makes it possible to
anonymously list containers without any read acl set if the metadata
"web-listings: true" is set on a container. Using make_env enforces correct
read_acl validation; however it is now also required to add ".rlistings" to the
read acl.

Also, if the staticweb middleware is put in the proxy pipeline before an
authentication middleware, it broke authenticated GET and HEAD requests. This
has some side effects in clients, because a html response is sent that might be
parsed wrongly by the client. In case of python-swiftclient this was shown as an
empty container without any ACL or web-listings:true meta set. This might lead
to information leaks, because a user trusts the output from python-swiftclient
and assumes an empty, private container even if the container contains public
readable data. staticweb now checks if "swift.authorize" is included in the
environ and skips itself if not.

commit_message:
Do not use pre-authenticated requests in staticweb

staticweb middleware uses make_pre_authed_env, this makes it possible to
anonymously list containers without any read acl set if the metadata
"web-listings: true" is set on a container. Using make_env enforces correct
read_acl validation; however it is now also required to add ".rlistings" to the
read acl.

Also, if the staticweb middleware is put in the proxy pipeline before an
authentication middleware, it broke authenticated GET and HEAD requests. This
has some side effects in clients, because a html response is sent that might be
parsed wrongly by the client. In case of python-swiftclient this was shown as an
empty container without any ACL or web-listings:true meta set. This might lead
to information leaks, because a user trusts the output from python-swiftclient
and assumes an empty, private container even if the container contains public
readable data. staticweb now checks if "swift.authorize" is included in the
environ and skips itself if not.

Closes-Bug: 1489749
Change-Id: Icf159d7e567ac5481e710c5910db686bdcba6336
Depends-On: Ie24bb995023c377e49796910ad80a256b00daa03

commit_message:
Show properties with empty values

Right now it is not possible to see image properties with
empty values(=None). So the patch add support of this
functionality for API v1. V2 already support this behaviour.

Change-Id: I5d17eb490f9e8c9c2c45f2a58a2a53e65142e181
Closes-bug: #1486115
