commit_message:
Set correct ACL for Swift staticweb tests

The staticweb middleware in Swift needs a small fix, and due to this one needs
to make listings public readable too when using staticweb listings.
This patch sets the correct ACL for this.

See also: https://review.openstack.org/#/c/227204/
Related-Bug: 1489749

Change-Id: Ie24bb995023c377e49796910ad80a256b00daa03

commit_message:
Correct the timestamp type when make test samples data

When recording samples to database, the timestamp should be
datetime.datetime type, but in make_test_data.py, the timestamp
will be transformed to iso format with unicode type.

Change-Id: Iffb09a293684fb8eab768c7370e8967349032ae5
Closes-Bug: #1504539

commit_message:
Handle py34 logging module

Py34 slightly modified how the logging module works [0]. Prior to the
3.4 release you could map strings to log levels and log levels to
strings. Now you can only map log levels to strings with public logging
methods.

Handle this in rootwrap by delaying errors when invalid log level names
are provided to where we set the log level. We still get a ValueError
this way it just happens further along in the code.

[0] http://hg.python.org/cpython/rev/5629bf4c6bba?revcount=60

Change-Id: I7b21120077676fbfabd4f77b1a347593cb51335b

I guess puppet uses etckeeper for a reason (presumably to update a set of config files in a transactional manner and to avoid conflicts with the package manager). I'm not quite sure disabling etckeeper is safe."}, {'account_id': 13948, 'date': '2015-10-21 08:09:09.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 6: Code-Review+1

Alexei, automatic etckeeper run is Ubuntu modification and is not done by vanilla Puppet. Additionally the package doesn't have hard dependency on etckeeper, so it makes sense to simply get rid of that "feature".'}, {'account_id': 13194, 'date': '2015-10-21 08:14:35.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 6:

> automatic etckeeper run is Ubuntu modification and is not done by vanilla Puppet.

This doesn't mean running etckeeper is something bad. Perhaps there are valid reasons to use etckeeper (like to prevent the package manager from trying to modify the config files managed by puppet)."}, {'account_id': 13948, 'date': '2015-10-21 08:17:08.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 6:

>like to prevent the package manager from trying to modify the config files managed by puppet

This is not what etckeeper does It initializes git repository in /etc and then saves all modifications with commits, that's all."}, {'account_id': 13194, 'date': '2015-10-21 10:04:08.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 6:

> This is not what etckeeper does

etckeeper hooks into APT to automatically commit changes made to /etc during package upgrades.'}, {'account_id': 12200, 'date': '2015-10-22 09:15:18.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 6: Code-Review+2

Could you please add a link to a passing BVT with this patch?'}, {'account_id': 7195, 'date': '2015-10-22 09:50:38.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 6: Code-Review+1'}, {'account_id': 7195, 'date': '2015-10-22 09:52:03.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 6:

Alexey: we are not implementing etckeeper at this time. Leaving its config there in place may mislead users. It's better to remove its references"}, {'account_id': 3009, 'date': '2015-10-22 09:58:59.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 6: Code-Review+2 Workflow+1

There are no objections from the cloud-init perspective. It just puts transparently prerun and postrun commands into puppet config. So, I leave this up to a library team to decide which config options they need to be in the puppet config file. There are couple +1s from library team, so I think we can merge this.'}, {'account_id': 3, 'date': '2015-10-22 09:59:04.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 6: -Verified

commit_message:
Disable launching etckeeper each puppet run

etckeeper is not installed or configured on deployed nodes, so it should
be replaced with a dummy command that will return 0

Change-Id: I0ced09f9cedcdb81eb3281168fed8b15f61d1e99
Closes-bug: #1504191

commit_message:
Fix wrong check with owner when create image

Now, when create image with owner in v2, it will raise a 403 error.
The reason is that glance doesn't get the 'owner' parameter with
right way.

Change-Id: I1b5bce2760465aee2791041f0f1b6797b8853f6f
Closes-bug: #1508359

revisions:
[{'created': '2015-08-14 08:28:11.000000000', 'message': 'test_db_base_plugin_v2: Avoid failures on OSX

netaddr produces different representations of
IPv4-compat addresses for different platforms.

Linux:
    >>> netaddr.IPAddress("::2")
    IPAddress('::2')
    >>>

OSX:
    >>> netaddr.IPAddress("::2")
    IPAddress('::0.0.0.2')
    >>>

While the use of IPv4-compat addresses here is questionable
to me, it's out of scope of this fix.

Closes-Bug: #1484837
Change-Id: Ib5b2b9bb6f81343ec497bff17392143b8b0c9652
'}]
commit_message:
test_db_base_plugin_v2: Avoid failures on OSX

netaddr produces different representations of
IPv4-compat addresses for different platforms.

Linux:
    >>> netaddr.IPAddress("::2")
    IPAddress('::2')
    >>>

OSX:
    >>> netaddr.IPAddress("::2")
    IPAddress('::0.0.0.2')
    >>>

While the use of IPv4-compat addresses here is questionable
to me, it's out of scope of this fix.

Closes-Bug: #1484837
Change-Id: Ib5b2b9bb6f81343ec497bff17392143b8b0c9652

[{'created': '2015-10-09 16:47:49.000000000', 'message': "Avoid division operation in shell

When the data returned from 'rabbitmqctl list_queues' grows a lot
and awk sums up all the rows especially for memory calculation it
returns the sum in scientific notation (example from bug
was .15997e+09), later when we want to calculate the memory in
MB instead of bytes, the bash division does not like this string.

We can just avoid the situation by doing the division into MB
in awk itself. Since we don't need the memory in bytes anyway.

Closes-Bug: #1503331
Change-Id: I38d25406b84d0f70ed62101d5fb5ba108bcab8bd
"}]
commit_message:
Avoid division operation in shell

When the data returned from 'rabbitmqctl list_queues' grows a lot
and awk sums up all the rows especially for memory calculation it
returns the sum in scientific notation (example from bug
was .15997e+09), later when we want to calculate the memory in
MB instead of bytes, the bash division does not like this string.

We can just avoid the situation by doing the division into MB
in awk itself. Since we don't need the memory in bytes anyway.

Closes-Bug: #1503331
Change-Id: I38d25406b84d0f70ed62101d5fb5ba108bcab8bd

Add request utils

project ever used it.

Adding it back because it will be required for mapping cross project
request ids. Openstack-spec is submitted for same
'Return request ID to caller' : https://review.openstack.org/#/c/156508/

commit_message:
Create shotgun project

This project is to provide a tool that is able to
collect logs, other files, command outputs, etc. that
can then be used for troubleshooting. I.e. it creates
a diagnostic snapshot for a set of nodes.

Change-Id: I366c95a293387fa17d769de49a66e10537e4b3ec

revisions:
[{'created': '2015-10-21 11:35:04.000000000', 'message': 'Change a bit order for generate_network_config

Now if we assign ip address to bridge - bridge is not ready due to there
are no ports in. This patch creates bridges and adds ports into it and then
assign ip address.

Was:
add-br(br-fw-admin) -> endpoint(br-fw-admin) -> add-br(br-mgmt) ->
endpoint(br-mgmt) -> add-port(eth0) -> add-port(eth0.101)

Now:
add-br(br-fw-admin) -> add-port(eth0) -> endpoint(br-fw-admin) ->
add-br(br-mgmt) -> add-port(eth0.101) -> endpoint(br-mgmt)

Change-Id: I902215c21dd512f1229c28a5a410d704755c27b8
Closes-bug: #1501459
'}, {'created': '2015-10-21 15:00:27.000000000', 'message': 'Fix ping default gateway error

Add noop tests

Change-Id: I902215c21dd512f1229c28a5a410d704755c27b8
Closes-bug: #1501459
'}]

commit_message:
Implement new random name generator for remaining scenario plugins

This switches all remaining scenarios to using the new consistent
random name generator. Keystone scenarios were switched in a previous
commit.

Implements blueprint: consistent-resource-names
Change-Id: I4d7defc328a516e7f84744c9a0fcaeb3b5f94d0c

commit_message:
Check for valid upstream git projects

This checks out the upstream git projects (unless we use track-upstream)
and prints some information about it.

Note this checks for all upstream repositories but since those are
cleaned up regularly, this should be fine.

It fails if the there is no remote master branch.

Reindent the original code as main function.

Change-Id: Ie469905f48e4bc1a408fb9e731f95b2b735a6a02

commit_message:
Fix error in stack-list metadata

In the --sort-keys option of the stack-list command, the metadata
lists keys separated by commas instead of semicolons.

Change-Id: I166d4dc48b97786a29c5d9ef6a5fb9411e80d6b1

Value: \'1.1\'. unable to convert to int"}'

Change-Id: I226e8f8c6afbbc94c6348a17099f02b9cf7907a8
Partially-Implements: blueprint mistral-py3

commit_message:
Add decode() function for string comparison.

A prefix of 'b' or 'B' is ignored in Python 2
But in py3 produce an instance of the bytes
type instead of the string type.

Due to which it gives following kind of error.
e.g.testtools.matchers._impl.MismatchError:
'unable to convert to int' not in
b'{"faultcode": "Client", "debuginfo": null,
"faultstring": "Invalid input for field/attribute limit.
Value: \'1.1\'. unable to convert to int"}'

Change-Id: I226e8f8c6afbbc94c6348a17099f02b9cf7907a8
Partially-Implements: blueprint mistral-py3

commit_message:
Fix migration from HA router to non-HA

When router migrates from HA to non-HA, neutron server doesn't
delete a relation between router and agents. This happens issue
that routers are created on multiple agents although it's non-HA.

This patch fixes the issue and adds a test case.

Change-Id: Icb1705c3774bb3bf434907ce4628d709ee67eff4

commit_message:
Remove deprecated sriov agent_required option

The SR-IOV option agent_required has been deprecated in Liberty.

This change removes it and from now agents are mandatory for SR-IOV
mechanism in order to support extended features: QoS, port security.

DocImpact
Closes-Bug: #1508182
Related-Bug: #1488807
Change-Id: I4e6497da6b287531a211084a5208028c84112a83

Add Cinder Extensions Service for Angular

to be a generically reusable extensions service.

commit_message:
Implement Component entity

This patch is part of works for implementation new mechanism of compatibility
between components in Fuel. Mechanism is based on 'component' entity. Current
changes provide ability to store compatibility data of components in DB:
'components' and 'release_components' tables, models and objects in Nailgun.

Implements: blueprint component-registry
Change-Id: I837ceb61d1858079c9a92eca5a2631bfd79c4f27

commit_message:
Add missing documentation for start_process_with_a_shell

This commit adds missing documentation for the plugin
"start_process_with_a_shell".  It also fixes a couple of typos in
"subprocess_popen_with_shell_equals_true" plugin doc.

commit_message:
Create network-checker project

This project is to provide functionality for network
connectivity health check. First we need to describe a network
connectivity graph (e.g. some nodes can send data to others via
tagged VLAN). We then can use this graph to check if network
equipment is configured according to the graph (i.e. we can
send probe data from one node and then to try to catch these
data on the other one).

Change-Id: I579c166aea07c7d52910a2723e740e16b0a7c052

commit_message:
Add remove-language-team script

To allow us to remove the Language-Team from every po file, since it
links to Transifex, and Zanata doesn't make use of the field -- and
therefore will not update it or change it, add a script that will
remove it from every po file in a given repository.

Change-Id: I7f73998043fe4e2d9aaab1618a0867a4865d7b94
Depends-On: I462354ecf9524e5f7d6a87ee954880bd2607854c

commit_message:
Mark abstractmethod bodies with nocover

abstractmethod bodies aren't going to be called by unit tests, so
there's no way to get coverage. The code in an abstractmethod body
should be marked with "# pragma: no cover" so that they don't show
up as missed in the coverage report.

Change-Id: I88a7481ab22f2ce1abfd62badc5f5048acc6929f

commit_message:
Fix incorrect ordering of install packaging section

Change https://review.openstack.org/#/c/237899/ reordered various
aspects of the environment sections in the install guide and
inadvertently re-ordered the packaging section.

As reported by Timo Henriksson, after installing the repositories,
the package list must be updated before clients can be installed.
If this is not done, incorrect and incompatible versions will be used.

Change-Id: Ifac6d788105f535cdddff3161d0691d50cc12d62
Closes-Bug: 1508409

commit_message:
Setup jobs for oslo.messaging pika driver

We need a couple of jobs for the feature/pika branch
of oslo.messaging to starting building up the new rabbitmq
driver using the pika library. Note that these jobs
should be voting false and should run just on the
branch.

Change-Id: I9bebdf556bb46bd75d8eb801250b14799974a65c

Add tarball-constraints jobs

This adds tarball constraints jobs and adds a new template section
that defines only the test jobs, while keeping the full set named
as expected.

Implements Blueprint: Requirements-Management

commit_message:
Support redirect when location not start with endpoint

There are some user cases will make the location
doen not start with endpoint, for example when using proxy
to redirect, the ip or port will changed: the endpoint is
http://10.10.0.22:8004/v1/tenant_id, the redirect location is
http://192.10.10.22:8104/v1/tenant_id/stacks/stack_name/stack_id.

Modify the logic to strip the location for these cases,
and now only to consider the location contains '/stacks'.

Change-Id: Ic7b025198c2d281c293ee5562e40a2d79fd37dbc
Closes-Bug: #1385581

commit_message:
Copy 'examples' to the output dir

Yaml files from 'examples' folder will be copied
to the root of the output folder. So, you can use
a relative path to them, for example:
`Linux network scheme <bonding_lnx_network_scheme.yaml>`_

Change-Id: Icf8ce065a1911e4fb1ef47bd8467ad73eed34359
(cherry picked from commit d903127d724b739bda56b1f9a50ae4d3bdbd0339)

commit_message:
replace git protocol by https

It will better to clone with https as "HTTPS works practically everywhere"
and 9418 port is blocked by many corporate firewalls.

Change-Id: I27edb8919af8ca3617bb50a305edfe7bbbe96836

commit_message:
Use Tempest-lib's compute fixed_ips_client

Compute fixed_ips_client has been migrated to tempest-lib-
Ic658f09649ed9498fe6d3e7792a7c370772f165b

Now Tempest-lib provides this client as stable interface so Tempest
should start using this from lib and remove its own copy.
Also remove other files for this client like response schema, unit tests.

This commits makes Tempest to use compute fixed_ips_client
from Tempest-lib.

Change-Id: Idce222bc2261e922973ff09878e9c065f5cdf4ec

usage: qemu-image convert

 I think qcow2 raw and QED VDI VMDK VHD at the same level,but qemu-img convert VMDK to qcow2,This is not the same, so this should be capitalized,line 54  line 58, I think.
thank you'}, {'account_id': 17106, 'date': '2015-10-21 07:43:52.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 5: Code-Review+1'}, {'account_id': 10497, 'date': '2015-10-21 11:56:51.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 5:

Just from my understand (non native English speaker).

It is reasonable to write an acronym in capital letter. So, "QCOW2" (QEMU Copy-On-Write 2) is reasonable.

However, we usually write non acronym word in small letter. Because "raw" is not an acronym, I think "raw" is reasonable.

This is not a whether all strings are same capital or not.

~~~~
On the other hand, as Tom mentined, this is the "qemu-img convert" context, so using the output of "qemu-img convert" is another reasonable approach. i.e. changing all to small letter.'}, {'account_id': 14101, 'date': '2015-10-22 02:11:40.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 5:

commit_message:
Change qemu-img convert formats

Convert between image formats,qcow2 raw and QED VDI VMDK VHD at the same level.
So,change the uppercase ones to lowercase.

Change-Id: I4f0cf310698bc89247c8024b782d1227432d4845

commit_message:
Copy 'examples' to the output dir

Yaml files from 'examples' folder will be copied
to the root of the output folder. So, you can use
a relative path to them, for example:
`Linux network scheme <bonding_lnx_network_scheme.yaml>`_

Change-Id: Icf8ce065a1911e4fb1ef47bd8467ad73eed34359

commit_message:
Remove file based queue support from scrubber

From Havana version glance was enhanced to be able to clean
pending-delete images up based on their location status db recorded [0],
the cleanup jobs were loaded from db instead of file based queue. So
from the release, we don't need file queue support for scrubber any
more. DB based queue allows scrubber centralized deplayment (for
active-active multi-instances model), but based on local file scrubber
can be deployed on single node only.

[0]
https://wiki.openstack.org/wiki/ReleaseNotes/Havana#Multiple_Image_Locations

Change-Id: I832cd786f3aa365b21f64ec429cea2f6b7c27dd4
Signed-off-by: Zhi Yan Liu <zhiyanl@cn.ibm.com>

commit_message:
[LBaaS v2] Improve API tests performance

API tests shouldn't require booting real nova instances and can be
limited by creating DB entities. That is why it is beter to use
noop drivers for Octavia in API tests as it allows to significantly
accelerate test runs.

Changing interval_time in _wait_for_load_balancer_status method
from 10 sec to 1 sec allows to decrease test execution time while
keeping the average number of retries low (0 or 1).
Removed excessive _wait_for_load_balancer_status calls in tests.

Fixed operations order in
test_update_load_balancer_missing_admin_state_up,
test_update_load_balancer_missing_description and
test_update_load_balancer_missing_name.

Fixed gate_hook to take into account recent changes to the
apiv2 job structure.

Depends-On: Ia26bd8cb28dccbb021b2a2f64a9b7e6ef498ff4c
Change-Id: I4a5ea91ed63ddcc1c560cde94bd7d461aca3c49e
Closes-Bug: #1498532
Closes-Bug: #1497471

Clarified DMVPN Pre-Shared Key (PSK) usages. 

Yanping - 

I didn't add the network-id yet to this spec. Did you had a chance to confirm more about network-id ?

Looking at the NHRP RFC [1] there is no explicit unique identifier required to be sent in the Registration Request / Reply. There is a Request ID that is auto-generated but that it a not related to the network-id required. 

I also found [2] that explains network-id is of local significance (local to a node) and there bit of confusion in its usage. Is this something you can handle just within the Cisco driver implementation for DMVPN ?

[1] https://tools.ietf.org/html/rfc2332
[2] https://supportforums.cisco.com/discussion/12075461/dmvpn-ip-nhrp-network-id"}, {'account_id': 3, 'date': '2015-06-08 20:19:09.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 7: Verified+1

commit_message:
Add Dynamic Multipoint VPN to Neutron VPNaaS

https://blueprints.launchpad.net/neutron/+spec/dynamic-multipoint-vpn

Enhance Neutron VPNaaS to support dynamic multipoint VPN using Next-
Hop Routing Protocol (NHRP).

Change-Id: I50998f70d4a1dcfea93e5e4ef9fbe2da0b1a19dc
Blueprint: dynamic-multipoint-vpn

commit_message:
Add unit test for test_servers_client-allfunctions

We have a plan to migrate service clients to tempest-lib from Tempest.
However, we are not doing enough tests for service clients now.
This patch adds unit test for test_servers_client (all functions)

Change-Id: I507b036bcdff4287b613d86b3fe18cd29a60e4d4

commit_message:
plugin_v2: Tighten network_type validation a bit

Instead of accepting any values, accept ours (midonet, uplink)
and what currently Horizon can send us without any attributes.
(local)

Closes-Bug: #1486943
Change-Id: Ib7824cda521393167771dee06baa6a23d88ac134

commit_message:
Add config reference autogeneration support for neutron-plugins

Adds entry to requirements/neutron-master.txt
    apicapi, pika for cisco plugin
    nuage for neutron itself
    github/pypowervm for powervm plugin
    pyroute2 for octavia plugin

With this fixes, almost problem for config-ref of neutron
is solved.
but another module problem is still requested to change
 apicapi             oslo.config issue
 kemptechnologies    oslo.config issue
 networking-ovs-dpdk __init__.py issue

Change-Id: Id193307f338f008858edf401fadf9ea9b260ac3c
Closes-Bug: #1503967
Related-Bug: #1507479

This makes sense based on the lock usage in get_access(), but I'm also wondering if the BaseIdentityPlugin is simply misbehaving in the first place? It seems it should release it's lock before re-authenticating."}, {'account_id': 7725, 'date': '2015-10-21 14:10:02.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 2: Code-Review-1

I'm not sure about this. This change makes the lock reentrant, but is that what we really want? Does this mean the auth posts may happen multiple times now?

IMO it would make more sense to see what actually caused this new recursion and fix that."}, {'account_id': 6486, 'date': '2015-10-21 15:00:56.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 2: Code-Review-1

This needs a unit test.'}, {'account_id': 4, 'date': '2015-10-21 15:48:30.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 2:

Brant: I don't think it's fair to demand tests here when you didn't require any here: https://review.openstack.org/#/c/221738/"}, {'account_id': 6486, 'date': '2015-10-21 18:03:16.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 2:

I've been trying to write a testcase for this and haven't had any luck.

Here's the code that the commit message says is being called[1]. Note that it will only invalidate() and then get_headers() and cause the deadlock if authenticated=True. authenticated can be passed in as False to the method to indicate that the request doesn't require authentication, and in the case of a request to get a token, authenticated is going to be False.

For example, in the case of the v3 plugins the call is session.post(token_url, ..., authenticated=False), see[2].

So the problem is likely that whatever plugin you're using isn't calling the Session.post() with authenticated=False rather than that this lock needs to be reentrant.

[1] http://git.openstack.org/cgit/openstack/python-keystoneclient/tree/keystoneclient/session.py#n389

[2] http://git.openstack.org/cgit/openstack/python-keystoneclient/tree/keystoneclient/auth/identity/v3/base.py#n189"}, {'account_id': 6486, 'date': '2015-10-21 18:07:16.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 2:

Dolph - the bug fixed in https://review.openstack.org/#/c/221738/ required multiple threads, which we don't have any existing tests for. Testcases for that would be nice but since we don't have existing multithreading tests I don't think it's worth it. The bug fixed here involves a single thread and we have lots of tests for that already."}, {'account_id': 1916, 'date': '2015-10-21 18:16:06.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 2: Code-Review-1

I agree with Brant, the plugins in python-keystoneclient seems to be calling Session.post() with authenticated set to False. This should not trigger the invalidate() call. If possible, can we put the thread dump or traceback in the bug?'}, {'account_id': 2813, 'date': '2015-10-22 05:53:26.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 2: Workflow-1

I have dump the backtrace and as you expect authenticated is False, the loop doesn't occurs like I have thought. I have to dig more :("}, {'account_id': 2813, 'date': '2015-10-22 05:53:57.000000000', 'content': 'Abandoned'}]

[{'created': '2015-10-21 11:42:31.000000000', 'message': 'Fix token lock race condition

BaseIdentityPlugin.get_access can be called recursively,
but the code is protected by a lock, so when this recursion occurs.
The lock hang the running thread.

The recursion occurs when:
* if needed, BaseIdentityPlugin.get_access() calls BaseIdentityPlugin.get_auth_ref()
* then the auth plugin uses Session.post(), that can calls (in case of 401)
  BaseIdentityPlugin.invalidate() and then
  BaseIdentityPlugin.get_headers()
* The last one, do BaseIdentityPlugin.get_access() again to get a new
  valid token. With a normal Lock() it stuck here.

This changes uses a RLock instead of a Lock to fix this.

Change-Id: I493199164694a17319a47525647a574363342fe6
Closes-bug: #1508424

commit_message:
Fix token lock race condition

BaseIdentityPlugin.get_access can be called recursively,
but the code is protected by a Lock(), so when this recursion occurs.
The lock hangs the running thread.

The recursion occurs when:
* if needed, BaseIdentityPlugin.get_access() calls BaseIdentityPlugin.get_auth_ref()
* then the auth plugin uses Session.post(), that can calls (in case of 401)
  BaseIdentityPlugin.invalidate() and then
  BaseIdentityPlugin.get_headers()
* The last one, does BaseIdentityPlugin.get_access() again to get a new
  valid token. With a normal Lock() it stuck here.

This changes uses a RLock instead of a Lock to fix this.

Change-Id: I493199164694a17319a47525647a574363342fe6
Closes-bug: #1508424

commit_message:
Add profile spec column in profile table

As the profile table has the profile type column, so we
only show spec properties while click the spec name,
and use table for properties.

Update screenshot: http://pasteboard.co/1cn4hr9j.png

commit_message:
[install] Fix cinder lock path

Fix cinder lock path to work around packaging bug.
Primarily applies to RDO, but shouldn't negatively
impact other distributions.

Change-Id: I06ad6ab1224ceb787b30ec4b2135c062a8b69e8d
Closes-Bug: #1490963
backport: kilo

Hi Atsushi,

Currently I'm struggling with generating the whole flagmappings file with the scripts available. This is why the headrs file is missing as only the common config options are included in the flagmappings file.

Let me know if you could help me with the scripts. :)

Thanks and Best Regards,
Ildiko"}, {'account_id': 17207, 'date': '2015-09-19 16:32:26.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 6:

First headers file is created manually.
Please make header file with refering like cinder, nova etc.'}, {'account_id': 17207, 'date': '2015-09-19 16:37:07.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 6:

Also Plese see following changes.
  https://review.openstack.org/#/c/224362/
He is try to merge config reference for manila (shared file systems).'}, {'account_id': 9562, 'date': '2015-09-19 16:38:01.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 6:

Hi Atsushi,

I know that it is created manually. The reason why I haven't created it yet is that the script does not include those config options in the flagmappings file that would require the headers file. I can create an empty file, but I need to figure out how to fix the script anyway to be able to add content to that file.

Best Regards,
Ildiko"}, {'account_id': 612, 'date': '2015-09-22 03:47:29.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 6:

Hi Ildiko,

Feel free to dump error messages here or on the docs mailing list and we'll help :)"}, {'account_id': 9562, 'date': '2015-09-22 10:06:12.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 6:

Hi Tom,

Thanks for support, I contacted Gauvain in mail, but it seems I only have more questions as before so I need to write a few more, maybe I'll cc the list too for the next one.

I started to check what I could do in the hooks.py file in openstack-doc-tools to make the situation better. Currently I'm not sure in what format I could register the config options in the right way as we removed the global cfg.CONF object from Aodh here: https://review.openstack.org/#/c/206573/2 And unfortunately the config gen script is based on the existence of that object. So I can manage to call the prepare_service() from the hooks file, but I'm still not sure on what to do with the local conf after that step. Any idea?

Thanks and Best Regards,
Ildiko"}, {'account_id': 612, 'date': '2015-09-22 10:20:52.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 6:

Ah.

That explains it.

Yeah, if the ops aren't registered in a global cfg.CONF object, that's going to make things pretty hard :)"}, {'account_id': 9562, 'date': '2015-09-22 10:25:16.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 6:

Hi Tom,

Yeah, I hear ya. :)

I guess I can hack it by reverting that commit from the local repo the script uses, but I can't do that in the future, so it would be good to figure out a more ling term solution. Although I don't really have the bandwidth neither the intention to rewrite the whole script. Is there a way to update the global object fro the hooks file? As the common options I have generated as you can see in this patch. The "only" thing that's missing is the newly added Aodh specific options.

Best Regards,
Ildiko'}, {'account_id': 9562, 'date': '2015-09-23 13:21:31.000000000', 'content': 'Uploaded patch set 7.'}, {'account_id': 9562, 'date': '2015-09-23 13:23:51.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 7: Workflow-1

Hi,

I still have issues with the script, namely that I have config options in the flagmappings file, which are not in aodh.conf. Has anyone experienced anything like this before?

Thanks and Best Regards,
Ildiko'}, {'account_id': 3, 'date': '2015-09-23 13:46:48.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 7: Verified+1

Ildiko,

I did a quick run of the script with your hooks patch. The additional options seems to come from the oslo libraries. But I might have missed something.'}, {'account_id': 9562, 'date': '2015-09-28 12:28:46.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 7:

Hi Gauvain,

Yeap, they're supposed to come from Oslo libraries. What I don't understand is that when I generate the aodh.conf file I don;t have these options. So I don't know now where the issue is originated.

Thanks and Best Regards,
Ildiko"}, {'account_id': 7923, 'date': '2015-09-28 19:43:12.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 7:

The only oslo module that is imported by autohelp, and not imported by the aodh config-gen script is oslo.middleware (if I'm not mistaken). commit_message:
Delete deprecated 'policy' option for webhook create

We don't support policy actions as of now, so the '--policy' option
makes no sense.

Change-Id: Ie22768831d5166d570311d2d4a35e423b9d7b52e

commit_message:
Added new rating module PyScripts

PyScripts can execute arbitrary Python code.

Code is stored in the database.
Every piece of code is loaded in memory and executed on the fly.
Code isolation is ensured so that only required data is modified.
Implemented gabbi tests.

Change-Id: Ieb7cd45e53078694603062e425451fa68dc0f791

Thank you for your first contribution to OpenStack.

    Your patch will now be tested automatically by OpenStack testing frameworks
    and once the automatic tests pass, it will be reviewed by other friendly
    developers. They will give you feedback and may require you to refine it.

    People seldom get their patch approved on the first try, so don't be
    concerned if requested to make corrections. Feel free to modify your patch
    and resubmit a new change-set.

    Patches usually take 3 to 7 days to be reviewed so be patient and be
    available on IRC to ask and answer questions about your work. Also it
    takes generally at least a couple of weeks for cores to get around to
    reviewing code. The more you participate in the community the more
    rewarding it is for you. You may also notice that the more you get to know
    people and get to be known, the faster your patches will be reviewed and
    eventually approved. Get to know others and become known by doing code
    reviews: anybody can do it, and it's a great way to learn the code base.

    Thanks again for supporting OpenStack, we look forward to working with you.

Build succeeded (check pipeline).

- gate-governance-docs http://docs-draft.openstack.org/92/194892/2/check/gate-governance-docs/093fde2//doc/build/html/ : SUCCESS in 49s'}, {'account_id': 4190, 'date': '2015-06-24 06:15:24.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 2: Code-Review+1 Rollcall-Vote+1'}, {'account_id': 1561, 'date': '2015-06-24 13:39:22.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 2: Code-Review-1 Rollcall-Vote-1

(1 comment)

I left one comment inline on the mission statement.

Akanda is effectively a backend for Neutron.  Every other Neutron backend is a sub-project under Neutron.  In some cases, it's just plugins to some system developed elsewhere, but not every case.  For example, we have Octavia as a full implementation of load balancing.  There's also the reference implementation of L2 and L3 features.

So, some questions...  

What makes Akanda different such that it should be its own independent project instead of a part of the Neutron project?

Can you discuss your collaboration with Octavia?  It seems there is complete overlap here with that.  Is it just that you see this as a more mature implementation of the same thing?  Has there been discussion of any collaboration or consolidation of effort on that part?

Regarding the name, I'm not sure if we have any problems, but I wanted to make sure others understand.  Akanda the project is driven by a company of the same name.  Does Akanda (the company) own the trademark?  This seems like a case we should check with the foundation to make sure this doesn't seem problematic."}, {'account_id': 3, 'date': '2015-06-24 13:45:07.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 2: Verified-1

Merge Failed.

This change was unable to be automatically merged with the current state of the repository. Please rebase your change and upload a new patchset.'}, {'account_id': 308, 'date': '2015-06-24 13:49:41.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 2: Code-Review-1

I'll say I'm not a big fan of using project names that match company names, and play on the confusion there.

OpenStack is an open collaboration space, and we strive to provide a level playing field to enable that. Having a project team which has the same name as a company imho prevents this level playing field.

I'm fine with a neutron-akanda repo under Neutron project team. I'm fine with Akanda Inc. being a large contributor to the Foobar project team. I don't agree with tilting the collaboration playing field by naming a project team by the trademarked name of a company."}, {'account_id': 2592, 'date': '2015-06-30 20:26:20.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 3: Commit message was updated'}, {'account_id': 3, 'date': '2015-06-30 20:26:27.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 3: Verified-1

Merge Failed.

At a glance I personally find it odd to apply for a top-level association to OpenStack if a project's foundation API is the Neutron's API. It doesn't matter how many new API's (extensions) are built on top of it, and how many projects exist to implement those backend services to realize those API's.

In other words, I'd be tempted to say that if you sign up to use the Neutron's API, you're part of Neutron no matter what you build around/on it. Can Astara work without Neutron? I.e: can it integrate with the rest of OpenStack without Neutron? From [1] I can't seem to justify why we'd want to have this type of membership for Astara.

My apologies if some of these statements/questions may sound silly, but I have add little time to ramp up in this discussion. My -1 is also about some discrepancies inline. I think we miss the necessary project-config patches that fill the dots.

[1] http://akanda.readthedocs.org/en/stable/architecture.html"}, {'account_id': 748, 'date': '2015-10-02 18:31:18.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 5:

FWIW if the two teams working on it are separate and one doesn't actively hurt the other, I don't see why we'd require that the Astara team dissolves itself into the Neutron team. 

There is no point in imposing external structure where it doesn't match the way contributing teams are organized. We made that mistake in the past with the "programs", and the Big Tent allows us to easily not make that mistake again.

Now if we think setting up Astara as a separate project team actively hurts Neutron, the TC has a call to make (value of adding Astara vs. damage to a critical component). But I don't see why that would be the case here ?'}, {'account_id': 1561, 'date': '2015-10-05 12:08:28.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 6:

I believe there is all around good intent here, but I'd like to do due dilligence around what Astara without Neutron means, since the intent to decouple the two is part of the plan here.  GBP was the last time a separate networking project applied, and after looking more closely into it, some (including me) felt it was harmful to Neutron.  I'm not claiming the same here, I just don't know yet, because it's something that doesn't exist yet.

Today, the project is very tied to Neutron.  Neutron sub-projects are already quite empowered and able to operate independently for much of what they do.  However, there is a general expectation within the Neutron community that these sub-projects *should* want to actively collaborate on the areas it makes sense.  They should be contributing to common APIs, testing, processes, and so forth.  If a team believes in this collaboration, I think actively *not* wanting to be a part of the larger "Neutron stadium" is concerning when that's how the rest of the Neutron community is structured.

The detail that makes this less clear to me is the potential future where Astara is not tied to Neutron, so that's the specific area I'd like to understand better.'}, {'account_id': 748, 'date': '2015-10-05 19:35:39.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 6:

(1 comment)'}, {'account_id': 2472, 'date': '2015-10-05 19:58:36.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 6:

Disclaimer: I'm a formal technical advisor to Akanda.

It seems like the expressed intent is to collaborate on areas, like the driver, where there is a lot of intersection with neutron but to maintain the implementation of the thing managed by the driver as a separate project. This is consistent with the way many other projects interface with neutron, isn't it? It's not clear why the main body of the project needs to be under the Neutron project's leadership, or why asking to have it standalone is being construed as being unwilling to collaborate. Surely we can't say that Mark hasn't contributed to Neutron?"}, {'account_id': 748, 'date': '2015-10-05 20:17:22.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 6:

(1 comment)'}, {'account_id': 1561, 'date': '2015-10-05 21:11:15.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 6:

@Doug

> "It seems like the expressed intent is to collaborate on areas, like the driver, where there is a lot of intersection with neutron but to maintain the implementation of the thing managed by the driver as a separate project. This is consistent with the way many other projects interface with neutron, isn't it?"

Yes, I understand the intent.  Comparing it to other projects isn't so clear cut.  First, not all backends are created equal.  They do varying degrees of implementing a thing vs. an interface to a thing.  Many are what you might consider a simpler interface to an external project.  Others I would consider much more of a full implementation of the thing.  In all cases though, every variant that's in OpenStack is under the Neutron.

This was actually quite a big discussion within Neutron during the last cycle.  We had to decide as a group whether or not we should organize as a set of sub-projects all unified under Neutron, or we would end up with a big list of separate project teams.  We went for unifying as sub-projects under Neutron and I'm trying to clarify why this would be the exception since again, this is not fundamentally different than other Neutron sub-projects, and would be the only one under Neutron.

The suggestion that Astara might make some sense outside of Neutron could be a good justification.  I just want to understand that better, since it seems to be a very early idea.  Armando's comment that coming in under Neutron and splitting out later if/when it makes sense seems quite reasonable to me.

> "It's not clear why the main body of the project needs to be under the Neutron project's leadership, or why asking to have it standalone is being construed as being unwilling to collaborate. Surely we can't say that Mark hasn't contributed to Neutron?

Hopefully the above explains where I'm coming from about being in Neutron vs not.  Of course Mark has contributed to Neutron.  I don't mean to imply any sort of bad intent here.  I just want to understand first what makes this different, because it's not yet clear to me.'}, {'account_id': 308, 'date': '2015-10-06 09:14:53.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 6: Code-Review+1 Rollcall-Vote+1

I don't buy the argument that because Neutron created the Neutron stadium, everything tied to Neutron cannot be a separate project team.

The Technical Committee judges project team additions, the fact that Neutron adopted a model that encourages projects to join under the Neutron project team doesn't really factor in.

What we need to judge is (1) whether the Astara project team is "one of us" (and I think they are) and (2) whether adding Astara as a separate project team is hurting Neutron so much that we'd rather keep Astara out of OpenStack (and I don't think they are).

We cannot force them to join under the Neutron project team -- the big tent was designed to abolish reserved territories and avoid forcing separate teams to arbitrarily merge. The two options on the table are "in" or "out" of OpenStack. Personally I think they should be in, for reasons outlined above.'}, {'account_id': 1561, 'date': '2015-10-06 11:00:31.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 6:

"(2) whether adding Astara as a separate project team is hurting Neutron so much that we'd rather keep Astara out of OpenStack (and I don't think they are)."

I don't think they are either, but it *could* be depending on what "Astara without Neutron" means, as discussed in the commit message.  I'd like to understand that a bit better.  In particular, "Astara via the driver model is capable of orchestration and management of services where the Neutron API is not available to tenants."  For example, does it mean exposing Astara's load balancing with a different/new LBaaS API?  It's not clear.'}, {'account_id': 2750, 'date': '2015-10-06 11:15:48.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 6: Code-Review+1 Rollcall-Vote+1

As someone that has spent time integrating bits of neutron into a coherence testing whole, I'm not really convinced that adding more to the neutron stadium is a path for success for either Neutron or new efforts, especially on the advanced feature side.

Personally, I'd much rather see the advanced services all stand as top level projects, instead of putting more things into the neutron stadium.

I feel like this effort's been around for a while. I'd like to see it using the ML to bring more folks in, as it's very single entity. But that doesn't seem any more of a stopper than any other projects we've moved forward."}, {'account_id': 105, 'date': '2015-10-06 13:21:29.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 6: Code-Review-1

I'd like to see Russell's questions answered here rather then just rubber stamping this."}, {'account_id': 748, 'date': '2015-10-06 13:53:17.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 6:

As PTL of a project where some people think we're clearly out of hope I think I have nothing else to add. So feel free to do whatever you want with this."}, {'account_id': 748, 'date': '2015-10-06 13:54:29.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 6:

None of my questions have gone acknowledged/answers, not sure what I am doing wrong.'}, {'account_id': 964, 'date': '2015-10-06 14:01:46.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 6:

I'll take a stab at Armando's Qs:

Can astara work without neutron? No, I'd say. I see it like the trove project; without nova it can't provision pre-configured databases. Without neutron, astara isn't collecting/gathering any networking layers. Tell me if that's correct.

Are there missing mappings for repos? Yes. Seems like http://git.openstack.org/cgit/stackforge/akanda-neutron needs renaming.

My grumpy morning personality says "ugh too complex please don't ask us to include this in the governance list as it causes difficulty in explaining "why" to both users and contributors." I'll try to come up with a better set of reasons such as API confusion and lack of commits in the open that I can uncover by this afternoon. 

Having to go to 180 days in metrics to show much activity is a concern about the active state of the project -- that we don't have much to go on to say it's really being worked in the open.'}, {'account_id': 748, 'date': '2015-10-06 14:13:11.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 6:

Thanks Anne, I am still getting familiar on how you guys review these changes...in Neutron-land we usually give +2/+1 thumbs-up only when we're happy that all outstanding items have been addressed, and no-one feels like he/she is been ignored/overruled."}, {'account_id': 308, 'date': '2015-10-06 14:52:46.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 6:

@Armando: in all cases we'll discuss it at the meeting today -- this won't get approved without a direct discussion, where I hope the Astara team will be able to give answers to the questions you raised.

Also my vote here is indicative and not final (as I suspect Russell's is). We only close the vote after the meeting (if a majority is reached)"}, {'account_id': 748, 'date': '2015-10-06 15:09:17.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 6:

Thierry, thanks for clarifying how the process works. Much appreciated. I'll try to make to the meeting."}, {'account_id': 2592, 'date': '2015-10-06 16:25:33.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 6:

(3 comments)

@annegentle Make sure to look at all of the repos for activity especially these [1] [2][3][4].   We have not renamed the repos to Astara because we were waiting to do the rename all at once the new name and governance location is determined.

As for API confusion, I do not think that this will be an issue.  The API is purely operational and internally focused and should not be exposed to regular users.  Our stance is that any changes to Neutron's public facing API should be enacted within Neutron.

[1] http://stackalytics.com/report/contribution/akanda-rug/180
[2] http://stackalytics.com/report/contribution/akanda-appliance/180

[4] https://review.openstack.org/#/q/status:open+project:stackforge/akanda-appliance,n,z"}, {'account_id': 1420, 'date': '2015-10-06 16:36:56.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 6:

@Anne, You shouldn't need to go 180 days in the past to find evidence of open development activity.  The akanda-neutron repo is less active than the others, please take a look through gerrit for a more accurate view of whats happening across the 3 current akanda repos: https://review.openstack.org/#/q/status:open+project:stackforge/akanda-appliance+OR+project:stackforge/akanda-appliance+OR+project:stackforge/akanda-rug+OR+project:stackforge/akanda-horizon+OR+project:stackforge/akanda-neutron,p,0037fb3800035b2f

RE: The question of APIs and a Astara+non-neutron:  Astara itself exposes no tenant facing APIs and we have no plans to introduce any. We have no plans to implement competing APIs for anything (networking or otherwise), or any new public APIs.  We currently rely on internal neutron messaging/notifications and the Neutron API in the Astara core, while drivers themselves are free to do whatever they need to orchestrate corresponding service appliances in the backend (your typical openstack driver model here).  I can't speak for Mark's intent WRT commit message in question, but  we've had some discussions about how/if it'd be possible to decouple Astara from Neutron itself to allow similar integration with other non-OpenStack systems (ie similar to standalone Ironic/bifrost), but we have no concrete plans on this front and might take some time exploring these ideas in Tokyo."}, {'account_id': 1561, 'date': '2015-10-06 16:49:38.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 6:

(1 comment)'}, {'account_id': 1561, 'date': '2015-10-06 17:05:57.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 6: -Code-Review -Rollcall-Vote

Thanks for the comments around the APIs, Adam.  With the clarification that there is no intention to build any new tenant-facing APIs for OpenStack, that resolves my major technical concerns about the separation of Astara from Neutron.

I still think it's worth considering being in Neutron, but I won't stay at -1 just on that point.  Ideally I'd like to see consensus reached between the Neutron PTL and Astara team on their plan."}, {'account_id': 748, 'date': '2015-10-06 19:26:03.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 6:

I see people keep pulling me in :)

I thought the major sticking points was: let's make sure that we leave no room to the perception that there is a double-standard for approving networking related projects under the big tent; because of the fact that today Astara is very tied to Neutron, and the fact that it's unclear what their future API will look like (lack of plan doesn't imply commitment not to interfere), I thought it was more sensible to bring this under the Neutron fold until things get cleared out/evolve over time. Do not get me wrong: I don't want this under the stadium as much as the Astara folks. I only thought that it was a sensible interim, to avoid calling 'foul play'. Should both of these issues be something the TC could be ok with, then I bow down.

I would personally be unease to approve something whose future shape I do not know, but it seems that this leap of faith is something ordinary in Big tent-land."}, {'account_id': 7, 'date': '2015-10-06 19:55:13.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 6: Code-Review+1 Rollcall-Vote+1

[{'created': '2015-06-24 00:35:49.000000000', 'message': 'Add Akanda to OpenStack Projects List

Following the directive http://governance.openstack.org/reference/new-projects-requirements.html

OpenStack Mission Alignment:
The Akanda project as outlined here https://wiki.openstack.org/wiki/akanda, is closely
aligned with the OpenStack mission of supporting public and private clouds while being easy
to implement and massively scalable. Akanda has been running at Dreamhost for over three
years running thousands of service instances. The project aims to have more public and
private clouds using Akanda before the end of the year.

Following the 4 opens
Open Source:
Akanda uses the open source Apache v2.0 license. Akanda does not have any library
dependencies that would restrict how the projects may be distributed or deployed.

Open Community:
The Akanda leadership is chosen by the contributors of the project. The current
PTL is sarob. The Akanda project has regular IRC meetings
https://wiki.openstack.org/wiki/Meetings/akanda and
everything is logged http://eavesdrop.openstack.org/meetings/akanda

Open Development:
- All code reviews are through the OpenStack infra CI
https://review.openstack.org/#/q/status:open+project:stackforge/akanda-appliance+OR+project:stackforge/akanda-appliance+OR+project:stackforge/akanda-rug+OR+project:stackforge/akanda-horizon+OR+project:stackforge/akanda-neutron,n,z
- Akanda has core reviewers https://review.openstack.org/#/admin/groups/682,members and
gate tests.
- The Akanda PTL acts as the liaison for cross-project teams
- Akanda collaborates with the OpenStack projects Oslo and Neutron.
- Akanda will contribute to Oslo as the opportunities arise.

Open Design:
- Akanda started holding public design meetings at the Kilo summit and will continue to do so.
- The Akanda team uses IRC and openstack-dev ML to discuss design

Basic OpenStack Project Interopability:
Akanda is compatable with OpenStack project APIs and reuses Oslo.

Active Team of Contributors:
Akanda has an active group of contributors

PTL is adam_g. The Astara project has regular IRC meetings
https://wiki.openstack.org/wiki/Meetings/akanda and
everything is logged http://eavesdrop.openstack.org/meetings/akanda

Open Development:
- All code reviews are through the OpenStack infra CI
https://review.openstack.org/#/q/status:open+project:stackforge/akanda-appliance+OR+project:stackforge/akanda-appliance+OR+project:stackforge/akanda-rug+OR+project:stackforge/akanda-horizon+OR+project:stackforge/akanda-neutron,n,z
- Astara has core reviewers
  https://review.openstack.org/#/admin/groups/682,members and
gate tests.
- The Astara PTL acts as the liaison for cross-project teams
- Astara collaborates with the OpenStack projects Oslo and Neutron.
- Astara will contribute to Oslo as the opportunities arise.

Open Design:
- Astara started holding public design meetings at the Kilo summit and
  will continue to do so.
- The Astara team uses IRC and openstack-dev ML to discuss design

Basic OpenStack Project Interopability:
Astara is compatable with OpenStack project APIs and reuses Oslo.

Common Questions:

Why is there a project name change?
The Astara team choose to select a new name to create a clear distinction
between entities providing commercial services and the project itself.
The new name was selected to further our original intent in placing this
project under governace -- a team open to all contributors.

Why seperate project?
The Astara team has choosen to seek status outside of Neutron because the scope
of the team will be more than the typical Neutron plugin/driver. The existing
repos within Neutron normally require code from external sources to provide the
implementation. Astara is different since the implementation will be
managed within the repo using the 4 opens.

Does Astara overlap with existing projects?
Astara implements network specific orchestration for logical resources managed
by tenants via the Neutron API, so it is natural for overlap to exist with
other implementations that provide load balancing, routing and/or VPN. Astara
is different from other projects currently under the OpenStack
namespace because it supports orchestrating a mix of Layer-3 through 7 network

possible we've reached out to other projects to work share code, exchange ideas

commit_message:
Add Astara to OpenStack Projects List

Following the directive
http://governance.openstack.org/reference/new-projects-requirements.html

OpenStack Mission Alignment:
The Astara project is to provide an integrated network service orchestration
for connecting and security multi-tenant OpenStack environments. Astara
provides deployer configurable multi-provider orchestration for Layer-3 through
7 network services (e.g. load balancing, routing). Astara (formerly called
Akanda) was designed from the beginning to integrate with OpenStack and further
OpenStack's mission. Astara features a driver based orchestrator to
orchestrate network functions from different providers on bare metal,
VMs and containers.  All core members have served the OpenStack community in
many ways such PTL, Stable Release management and critical 3rd party library
maintainers. Astara has been open source and in production since Grizzly.

Following the 4 opens
Open Source:
Astara uses the open source Apache v2.0 license. Astara does not have any
library dependencies that would restrict how the projects may be distributed
or deployed.

Open Community:
The Astara leadership is chosen by the contributors of the project. The current
PTL is adam_g. The Astara project has regular IRC meetings
https://wiki.openstack.org/wiki/Meetings/akanda and
everything is logged http://eavesdrop.openstack.org/meetings/akanda

Open Development:
- All code reviews are through the OpenStack infra CI
https://review.openstack.org/#/q/status:open+project:stackforge/akanda-appliance+OR+project:stackforge/akanda-appliance+OR+project:stackforge/akanda-rug+OR+project:stackforge/akanda-horizon+OR+project:stackforge/akanda-neutron,n,z
- Astara has core reviewers
  https://review.openstack.org/#/admin/groups/682,members and
gate tests.
- The Astara PTL acts as the liaison for cross-project teams
- Astara collaborates with the OpenStack projects Oslo and Neutron.
- Astara will contribute to Oslo as the opportunities arise.

Open Design:
- Astara started holding public design meetings at the Kilo summit and
  will continue to do so.
- The policy of the Astara team is to use IRC and openstack-dev ML to discuss
  design. At this time, the public IRC channel, Launchpad and Gerrit are
  the primary locations where discussions occur.

Basic OpenStack Project Interopability:
Astara is compatable with OpenStack project APIs and reuses Oslo.

Common Questions:

Why is there a project name change?
The Astara team choose to select a new name to create a clear distinction
between entities providing commercial services and the project itself.
The new name was selected to further our original intent in placing this
project under governace -- a team open to all contributors.

Why not the Neutron stadium?
The Astara team is concerned our setup will create an additional burden
on the Neutron team due to the differences relative to other stadium
projects.

- Astara currently has 3 respostiories for code that are designed to
  integrate with projects other than Neutron and 1 Neutron driver repo. The
  current Neutron Stadium members have only 1 repository each and the repo
  directly integrates with Neutron.
- Astara provides a sepearate management cli and RPC API not connected to
  Neutron REST API. Our tenantative plans for the upcoming cycle includes
  expanding the capabilities of the administrative cli tools and API.
- Astara via the driver model is capable of orchestration and
  management of services where the Neutron API is not available to
  tenants.  The team plans to investigate this further during the next two
  cycles.

Does Astara overlap with existing projects?
Astara implements network specific orchestration for logical resources managed
by tenants via the Neutron API, so it is natural for overlap to exist with
other implementations that provide load balancing, routing and/or VPN. Astara
is different from other projects currently under the OpenStack namespace
because it supports orchestrating a mix of Layer-3 through 7 network
functions via baremetal, VMs and containers from within a single service. Where
possible we've reached out to other projects to share code, exchange ideas
and explore joint development. The Astara team has been present online
and at the Neutron and Advance Service mid-cycles for the previous two years
to promote a close working relationship with the community.

Active Team of Contributors:
Astara has an active group of contributors
http://stackalytics.com/report/contribution/akanda/180
http://stackalytics.com/report/contribution/akanda-rug/180
http://stackalytics.com/report/contribution/akanda-appliance/180
http://stackalytics.com/report/contribution/akanda-horizon/180
http://stackalytics.com/report/contribution/akanda-neutron/180

CGSnapshot Object

This patch adds VersionedObjects abstraction layer to CGSnapshots.

Co-Authored-By: Szymon Wroblewski <szymon.wroblewski@intel.com>
Co-Authored-By: Michal Dulko <michal.dulko@intel.com>

Partial-Implements: blueprint cinder-objects
Change-Id: Ie4cdd1ffae15a93bff756ad278ca680f9f420748

commit_message:
root_on_create for Couchbase should be false

Currently all Couchbase datastores that are created enable
root and return a root password on the call. This shouldn't
be the default. This commit changes the default for Couchbase
to false.

Change-Id: Id0099bc55d6bab4f63001d3b20ded37b3db901c4
Closes-bug: 1507137

commit_message:
Couchbase cluster-init command needs credentials

During the prepare call in the Couchbase guest, it executes
couchbase-cli cluster-init. This command requires database
credentials to be passed in with -u and -p.

This commit adds these options to the command line.

Change-Id: I3a6b9268e045e7f646cd83dd4fdff992d23aedf0
Closes-bug: 1496189

commit_message:
Rely on pbr to define the version of the library

Pbr has a way to create the library version based on last tag. If
current commit does not match with the tag, it adds the PEP 440
compliance value devXXX where XXX is the number of commits after the
last tag, highlighting that it is a development version.

Before 2015.1, MidoNet had tags not recognized by pbr. However, adding
the PKG-INFO file we could trick pbr to set the version number we
wanted.

Now we are pbr and PEP440 compliance, so we can rely on 'pbr' to create
this version. It is time to improve setup.cfg and delete the PKG-INFO
file, which will be generated by the `pbr` tool.

Change-Id: Id3d83611ba2d87467a5d522891b6dd5f83e8f9a6

commit_message:
Use assert(Not)In instead of assertTrue/False

Neutron tests should use:

self.assertIn(value, list) and
self.assertNotIn(value, list)

instead of:

self.assertTrue(value in list) and
self.assertFalse(value in list)

because assertIn and assertNotIn raise more meaningful errors:

self.assertIn(3, [1, 2])
>>> MismatchError: 3 not in [1, 2]

self.assertTrue(3 in [1, 2])
>>> AssertionError: False is not true

To enforce this improvement, this patch is created.

Change-Id: Ia2ca003829858cceda181da41dea4f70a3d48d45
Related-Bug: #1218713

commit_message:
Add doc8 to pep8 job

To allow doc8 testing of the Magnum documentation in CI, doc8 should be
added to the pep8 tox command. After discussion with infra (see change
I6d42cb2092cbaed0cc2ed83f23b7f9ce0b52356f) this has been the suggested
method to allow for doc8 style checking.

As this behaviour is non-obvious I have left the doc8 command in the doc
tox env, this is not run by CI but will be run by users when modifying
and compiling documentation.

Change-Id: I93133e92d792ccc13d61f3ad1281007c2639853b

exception in a transaction, see sqlalchemy faq
http://docs.sqlalchemy.org/en/rel_0_8/faq.html#this-session-s-transaction-has-been-rolled-back-due-to-a-previous-exception-during-flush-or-similar .
There are places in Neutron code where a db exception is caught and
the session is not properly rolled back.

commit_message:
Handle DB exception correctly within a transaction

This patch addresses two issues: roll back the session after
catching a DB exception and use session.begin_nested() to
frame an operation that might fail within a transaction to be able to
roll back to the point before its failure while maintaining the
enclosing transaction.
For more details see sqlalchemy faq
http://docs.sqlalchemy.org/en/rel_0_8/faq.html#this-session-s-transaction-has-been-rolled-back-due-to-a-previous-exception-during-flush-or-similar .

Change-Id: I04533fa64d7214234ce9fd6564616db9a989fee0
Closes-Bug: #1409774

Add angular flavors panel

Adding a new panel to the admin dashboard that will use angular js
instead of the django templates

To test set DISABLED = False in _2081_admin_flavors_panel.py

Partially-Implements: blueprint ng-flavors

commit_message:
Add pxe_irmc driver support into os-cloud-config

The pxe_irmc driver has been introduced into Ironic at Kilo,
and this patch will add this driver into os-cloud-config.

Change-Id: I271f4cb1fdf991be4ed669c0c1061f13acb5168f
Closes-Bug: 1462260

commit_message:
Fix for vnfd-delete with vnfd-name as arg

When deleting a vnfd using vnfd-name as argument it returns
'descripton' string, if db has multiple entries with same name.
This patch fix this problem by checking the existence of key
'description' in 'vnfd' dict.

Change-Id: I3c350ec1b563b1933df93106717f373afc368146
Closes-Bug: #1508174

commit_message:
Include alembic versions directory to the package

If package is built without access to git metadata, all the migration
scripts are not included in the build. We need to explicitly specify to
package the scripts.

Change-Id: I9a2acad13271863ee94de63c2404e8697ea70601
Closes-Bug: #1505628

commit_message:
Switch to maintained RA repository

github.com/madkiss/openstack-resource-agents is no longer maintained.
Use the new repository under the OpenStack umbrella for the resource
agents.
Also use git.openstack.org instead of github.com .

Change-Id: I0bda307d4e074a01f2d70c1ca08ba6ee5eb20f37

commit_message:
Remove CredentialProvider deps to CONF

CredentialProvider uses CONF to get identity_version.
Identity version is always passed in anyways, so removing the CONF
dependency and making identity_version a mandatory parameter,
so that the class is ready for migration to tempest-lib

Partially implements: bp tempest-library
Change-Id: Ia960bf0b293e23537b3aaa8114bdbf7a46db62b1

commit_message:
Remove unnecessary <base> tag.

The <base> tag improperly overrode the base path for relative
resources in our environment. As we instead need the default
browser behavior for relative resources, this removes the
directive.

Change-Id: I37926814c4958d5fa10f6484071d1f93a06a88fd

commit_message:
ASG scaling account for cooldown timestamp & in-progress

There are cases where it takes a long time to create a new resource as
requested by the scaling operation on an ASG resource, for instance, a
nova server creation followed by a complex SoftwareDeployment. During
this process, additional alarms may come in but failed to be blocked
by the current cooldown checking mechanism because the very first
timestamp has yet to be generated. This is leading to unexpected size
adjustment to the ASG.

This patch augments the existing cooldown checking mechanism with a
scaling-in-progress test so that additional alarms arriving during
the very first scaling operation will be ignored.

Change-Id: Ib8aa83eed366df7097c9cbb9247eca866ae4b620
Co-Authored-By: Zane Bitter <zbitter@redhat.com>
Closes-Bug: #1375156

commit_message:
Group role revocation invalidates all user tokens

Keystone invalidates every token for a user after revoking one group role
within one project.

This patch replaces 'invalidate user's everything' logic with revocation by
grant via notifications for delete_grant assignment operation.

Closes-Bug: #1402760
Closes-Bug: #1401926
(cherry picked from commit 2cf743d6de3afcb1a0aa3d4c219b3c4bcea29008)

There was one conflict fixed by hand in core.py. The test case had to be
adjusted as driver='kvs' and driver='uuid' (test_v3_auth.py)
will not work in the stable/kilo release.

# Conflicts:
#>------keystone/assignment/core.py

Change-Id: If9d0fefe43da96ba5e6b6ffc809b9f15e8d732f7

revisions:
[{'created': '2015-10-14 01:18:16.000000000', 'message': "Introduces the Pez instance provider

This abstracts away how/where akanda.rug.api.nova.boot_instance()
creates a new resource.  It preserves existing behavior of booting
one-off instances for resources in the OnDemandInstanceProvider.

It introduces a PezInstanceProvider which relies on a new service
akanda-pez-service.  This service is responsible for keeping pools
of hot-standby nodes to be ready for use as appliance VMs.  The size
of said pools are configurable and it maintains separate pools for
each enabled driver type.

When configured with the the PezInstanceProvider, the Rug will request
instances via RPC from Pez instead of booting directly from Nova.

To enable, you must run the akanda-pez-service and then set
'instance_provider=pez' in rug.ini.  The default, which preserves existing
behavior, is 'instance_provider=on_demand'

Implements: blueprint nodepool-support

Change-Id: I7680c747d8c351c63d675f5fb377eee5edbf7b31

commit_message:
Introduces the Pez instance provider

This abstracts away how/where akanda.rug.api.nova.boot_instance()
creates a new resource.  It preserves existing behavior of booting
one-off instances for resources in the OnDemandInstanceProvider.

It introduces a PezInstanceProvider which relies on a new service
akanda-pez-service.  This service is responsible for keeping pools
of hot-standby nodes to be ready for use as appliance VMs.  The size
of said pools are configurable and it maintains separate pools for
each enabled driver type.

When configured with the the PezInstanceProvider, the Rug will request
instances via RPC from Pez instead of booting directly from Nova.

To enable, you must run the akanda-pez-service and then set
'instance_provider=pez' in rug.ini.  The default, which preserves existing
behavior, is 'instance_provider=on_demand'

Implements: blueprint nodepool-support

Change-Id: I7680c747d8c351c63d675f5fb377eee5edbf7b31

commit_message:
Disable migration sanity check

Disable the migration sanity check, it has served to wedge deployers
more often than anything and should (instead) issue a warning that
the deployer should fix their table. Until the real fix is in place
just disable it for any keystone migration.

Change-Id: I210dcc77d188ae3b505dccdac1534184b8443aa9
closes-bug: #1469029
(cherry picked from commit daecabcda752004b760c5be5a4a3a4d5471554db)

commit_message:
Install Guide Cleanup

This commit does the following:

- sets all shell prompts in code-blocks to the root prompt
- uses shell-session code-block since the shell prompt was being
  treated as a comment
- other minor cleanup

(cherry picked from commit 06708191d6bfaf627f8f0a51f1c90cb06c20f2f4)

Conflicts:
	doc/source/install-guide/configure.rst
	doc/source/install-guide/configure-aodh.rst
	doc/source/install-guide/configure-ceilometer.rst
	doc/source/install-guide/install-foundation-run.rst

Change-Id: I9e3ac8bb0cabd1cc17952cfd765dbb0d8f7b6fa2

commit_message:
Allow configration of config_drive_format inside nova.conf

This patch adds the nova override nova_config_drive_formats which
defaults to iso9660. This override can be individually configured
over the `user_variables`. Additionally the packages
dosfstools-dbg dosfstools are installed in case the
config_drive_format vfat is used

Change-Id: I313bf05b814def16527bce74a5c6d3ece9044146
Closes-Bug: #1489225

commit_message:
Change section name for AMQP qpid parameters

According to docs for liberty and kilo [1,2] should be
section 'oslo_messaging_qpid' instead of 'DEFAULT'.

[1] http://docs.openstack.org/liberty/config-reference/content/configuring-rpc.html
[2] http://docs.openstack.org/kilo/config-reference/content/configuring-rpc.html

Change-Id: I9207f2edc91cfd3e3553971e00e1510c83d0f7b9

[{'created': '2015-10-21 04:46:45.000000000', 'message': 'Fix TypeError when listing agents for HA router

It looks like a race condition is induced by this fullstack
test where, when creating an HA router, the agents are not
yet bound to the router, hence triggering the exception.

This patch ensures that we only return non-None bindings
and the test is made more robust to timing factors.

Change-Id: Ifa72b5a5adb9f3f6c114a1a2afaccea3605e3901
Closes-bug: #1508261
'}]
commit_message:
Fix TypeError when listing agents for HA router

It looks like a race condition is induced by this fullstack
test where, when creating an HA router, the agents are not
yet bound to the router, hence triggering the exception.

This patch ensures that we only return non-None bindings
and the test is made more robust to timing factors.

Change-Id: Ifa72b5a5adb9f3f6c114a1a2afaccea3605e3901
Closes-bug: #1508261

commit_message:
Stop validating pre-provisioned credentials

Stop validating pre-provisioned credentials when requested
within the credential provider. This drops the need for
estabilishing connection to the identity service, and
reduces the amount of configuration that has to be passed
into the credentials provider for it to work.

This work is in preparation to the migration of the
pre-provisioned credentials provider to tempest-lib.

Change-Id: I825a01ff72cb3a937aafeb2104333db7113ef4d0

commit_message:
Adds unit tests for datasetservice, homeCtrl

Alters main.js to allow Karma to see app. Basic unit tests (checking
for definition) are added as placeholders. New unit test files will
need to have the window.bootstrap && window.bootstrap() call to allow
Karma visibility.

Change-Id: If3ad2130e6ad6e3883a57ddd291fc17753229ed8

commit_message:
Document how to use network isolation/static IPs

This patch adds a file documenting the use of isolated networks with static
IP addresses. This optional functionality allows the use of static IP addresses
on networks based on function: internal API, tenant, storage, storage management,
and external/public API.

Co-Authored-By: Dan Sneddon <dsneddon@redhat.com>

Change-Id: I34e652a3bd347b3e749b12bdc11e4e370e372db4

update about all the noise here ... i've been trying to get this to pass tempest, and naturally, i get inconsistent behavior between my local env and the gate env.

The biggest issue I'm fighting right now is DHCP not working with ACLs enabled.  I have a hack in the neutron plugin now trying to work around it, but it doesn't always work.  I don't know why it does sometimes and not others.  I think it has to do with state in conntrack at the time.

I'm going to revisit this with some fresh eyes in the morning and I may try another workaround by hacking OVN itself to put some custom flows in that bypass conntrack if it looks like DHCP.

Someone is also working on native distributed DHCP support in OVN, which means it'll work totally different soon.

Anyway ... that's it for tonight."}, {'account_id': 3, 'date': '2015-10-21 01:38:30.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 24: Verified-1

commit_message:
Add security group support using OVN ACLs.

This patch implements Neutron security groups by creating the
appropriate ACLs in the OVN_Northbound database.  OVN ACLs are
implemented using conntrack integration with OVS.

All of the OVN and OVS code is merged into master, but it requires
kernel support which has not yet been merged into the in-tree kernel
module in OVS.  There's a branch that has the kernel backport available,
so this patch also switches the default branch we test against to one
where the kernel backport is available.

The patch includes some TODOs and some bug reports for disabled tests,
though not all necessarily related to this patch.

Related-bug: #1457567
Change-Id: I71d59dcab3f8b52adb734308df7ac97e2fa0d1b4
Signed-off-by: Russell Bryant <rbryant@redhat.com>

revisions:
[{'created': '2015-10-21 20:28:00.000000000', 'message': "Stop trying to set defaults with the prescribed method

The config parser docs say you should set default values for missing
config options by passing in a dict to the parser init which will be
interpolated when a non-existent option is used. However, in practice
this either completely didn't work in the case of my local testing, or
in the case of the production server it tried to use it but couldn't
deal with the int values. This commit just drops the use of the dict
and uses the try except catch brute force approach which was added
to workaround the issues with local testing. It's not pretty, but
it at least works.

Change-Id: Ic335ace8339b5f2ac07ba8fcf8ad125e1f816ae9
"}]
commit_message:
Stop trying to set defaults with the prescribed method

The config parser docs say you should set default values for missing
config options by passing in a dict to the parser init which will be
interpolated when a non-existent option is used. However, in practice
this either completely didn't work in the case of my local testing, or
in the case of the production server it tried to use it but couldn't
deal with the int values. This commit just drops the use of the dict
and uses the try except catch brute force approach which was added
to workaround the issues with local testing. It's not pretty, but
it at least works.

Change-Id: Ic335ace8339b5f2ac07ba8fcf8ad125e1f816ae9

Start Monasca API as non-daemon

Start Monaca API as non-daemon process. This is so that
Upstart can keep track of the process and manage it.

commit_message:
Ensure ping returns after 5mins timeout

This change ensures the validation script returns (with a failure)
if the ping command remains stuck waiting for a response for more
than 5 minutes.

Change-Id: Ib184a01e04fe3c5e3ad13757a355735fff84548d

commit_message:
Fix rspec unit & beaker tests

Problem #1
https://review.openstack.org/#/c/228744/ has been merged, we need to
drop the 'tenant' parameter to Keystone_user resource.

Problem #2
https://review.openstack.org/#/c/228744/ has been merged, we need to
drop the '_member_' role management.

Change-Id: I22313fed2c9f2c07caa6058e615d3872e0cfb861

commit_message:
Make connection pool settings configurable

When running the api server in production we're seeing a dropped
connection causing 500 responses and the server never recovering
from this. This commit attempts to address this by making the
connection pooling settings configurable and setting better defaults
which will result in not dropping all requests after 1 db connection
timeout.

Change-Id: I1be350794651eb8ec544c0626bb9d516d7efef1b

commit_message:
Fix karma-coverage version, use `gulp unit` to run unit tests

Downgrades karma-coverages, uses phantomJS to run unit test, and
finally adds gulp unit as the test runner. Karma was having issues
with Chrome+Browserify. Unit tests still do not run since the example
services were removed.

Change-Id: I8973a1e12b0b2af992bea5da552aae0736dcdf9c

commit_message:
Update module install scripts from master

There are more than 10 commits that we would have to backport, while we
were still trying to stabilize the scripts.

Instead of doing all these backports, let's just synchronize the scripts
for once, so we can use install_modules_unit.sh in puppet-* modules.

Change-Id: Ifdaead47689fb596e0b847b133acbcb0b444b1a3

(3 comments)

This patch does not fix the bug that the requester identified. (https://bugs.launchpad.net/manila/+bug/1496010)

When Share instances were introduced, we decided to make the drivers agnostic of the feature. In the share data that the driver receives at various entry points, it is made to believe that the 'id' it gets is the share_id. This isn't true. 

for example, in the create_share call, parameter share contains the data the driver needs to create the share, but:
share['id'] is actually the share_instance_id
share['share_id'] is the actual share_id

Thank you for proposing this fix. If you want to 'fix' this bug, I would suggest taking this to the logs at manila/share/manager.py or within manila/share/driver.py. 

We cannot expect every individual driver to know/enforce this type of logging, because they should not know/care what share instances are."}, {'account_id': 18128, 'date': '2015-10-20 13:36:44.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 1:

For rechecking only on the Microsoft Manila CI, add a review comment with check microsoft_manila_ci

abandoning this fix as it was not correct'}]

commit_message:
use cp always instead of mv / cp logic

Grenade was not getting cached files on the old side, leading to
higher failure rates as it talks to the internet for things like the
cirros images. Part of this is because there is conditional mv / cp
logic that might have worked once, but doesn't now.

In order to address space concerns, do the following:

mv the cache files to $BASE/cache/files (which is typically going to
be /opt/stack/cache/files), this should be on the same filesystem as
devstack / grenade in all of our cloud providers.

cp -l from this new cache to where the devstack / grenade caches
should be. This means we'll still only have 1 copy of the bits in the
filesystem, now with a number of hardlinks to it.

Closes-Bug: #1507533

Change-Id: Ie09e1671329c4144be85af71ea892246b81fdad3

commit_message:
Support multiple addresses assignment with eni

Currently only the first IPv4/v6 address is assigned to a NIC
even if multiple addresses are specified in config file.
With this change, eni implementation can configure multiple
IPv4/v6 addresses for a NIC.
Also this fixes IPv6 netmask format, which currently causes
an error on ifup.

Change-Id: I0a38d376bece8af297bddede594962fd3a193d09

commit_message:
Fix race condition in stack listing

When listing stacks, we first load them from the database, and then we
load their template in a different transaction. If a stack is deleted in
the mean time, loading the template will raise a NotFound exception, and
will make the listing returns NotFound, instead of ignoring that stack.
This patch handles the exception and continue to try to load stacks.

Change-Id: Iba6db81e3c10310955928fe723b84b5f62fc3fc1
Closes-Bug: #1508390
