commit_message:
Optionally disable fip reuse

Reusing floating IPs with nodepool could be prone to race conditions.
Floating IPs are also not always reusable -- one of the few positive
things about them is that you can use them for service addresses that
move between machines.  It would be very bad to reuse them in that
case.

This change starts making floatip IP reuse optional, at least in
the nodepool path.  It should probably be extended for other code
paths as well.  It should be considered for default behavior as well.

commit_message:
Test networking-bgpvpn master vs. stable/liberty

There were confused discussions aroung change
I049a521b4e948a042c9b49eaecd9399cf84353d1 which added
a first gate job for networking-bgpvpn, more precisely
on how to do the right thing with branches.

The intent is the following, and wasn't made clear earlier:
networking-bgpvpn is release-independent, and currently has
no stable/liberty branch ; until it forks a stable/liberty
branch we want its master branch to be tested against
stable/liberty of Neutron, devstack, and all Openstack components.

This change implements this intention, as confirmed with
clarkb on IRC:

http://eavesdrop.openstack.org/irclogs/%23openstack-infra/latest.log.html#t2015-10-12T15:17:53

Change-Id: I983d3af9b40160c4bbfec683cd4eb17dd46ee1db

I don't thinks it's a stupid question Assaf. The goal, in my mind, is to develop this Docker libnetwork driver in a neutron repo but not the main neutron repo itself."}, {'account_id': 8873, 'date': '2015-08-17 17:05:02.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 4:

Why does it need a spec then?'}, {'account_id': 6836, 'date': '2015-08-17 18:54:05.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 4:

(3 comments)'}, {'account_id': 11343, 'date': '2015-08-18 07:29:07.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 4:

Assaf, there is no need for Kuryr to be in the neutron tree, however Kuryr is a "gateway" for other projects that want to leverage Neutron with containers networking (some internally and some that already use Neutron plugins with their own solution)

We wanted to publish it here so everyone can view and approve the use cases to see we don't miss anything.

(And i suspect we might need to adjust or be in the loop of some of Neutron API's specs, but thats a future goal)

For now, if somone think there is a better place to put this, i am open for suggestions :) i preferred to put it in a place with more visibility then the Kuryr repo as we are representing Neutron with this project and its not yet another plugin implementation.'}, {'account_id': 11343, 'date': '2015-08-19 11:10:39.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 3:

commit_message:
Port test_wsgi to Python 3

* Replace filter() with list-comprehension to get a list on Python 3.
* HTTP body type is bytes: use byte strings for body.

Change-Id: Ia7fba4b075cdedd4581e4e8503f5220c1e6198d7

[{'created': '2015-10-21 15:33:07.000000000', 'message': 'pass on @abc.abstractmethods

Although a bare docstring is entirely valid grammar, those new to Python find
that pattern baffling, *especially* when other similar methods contain pass
statements. So, for consistency, add a pass statement to otherwise bare
@abc.abstractmethods.

Note that the implementation of an @abc.abstractmethod (in the abstract
base class) can still be called by concrete children, so suddenly
raising a NotImplementedError() instead might be "surprising" to
implementors. A no-op such as "pass" or "return None" is preferable.

Change-Id: I79969ad1a3429516ea785c649a165ead54944225
'}]
commit_message:
pass on @abc.abstractmethods

Although a bare docstring is entirely valid grammar, those new to Python find
that pattern baffling, *especially* when other similar methods contain pass
statements. So, for consistency, add a pass statement to otherwise bare
@abc.abstractmethods.

Note that the implementation of an @abc.abstractmethod (in the abstract
base class) can still be called by concrete children, so suddenly
raising a NotImplementedError() instead might be "surprising" to
implementors. A no-op such as "pass" or "return None" is preferable.

Change-Id: I79969ad1a3429516ea785c649a165ead54944225

commit_message:
DVR: Notify specific agent when update floatingip

The L3 agent was determined when update floatingip.
So notify the specific agent rather than notify all agents.
This will save some RPC resources. This is only for DVR routers.
Legacy and HA routers notify only the relevant agents.

This reproposes commit 52e91f48f2327b47f126893f9cb12f153380a9a6
which was reverted by commit a2f7e0343a147a30a637af4e1cb9a866f557e87d
because of Ironic gate failures.
Now the patch preserves original behavior for legacy routers and
should not break Ironic tests.

Partial-Bug: #1486828
Related-Bug: #1507602
Change-Id: I4ef7a69ad033b979ea0e29620a4febfe5e0c30dd

commit_message:
proposal to add Ryota Mibu to Aodh core

i'd like to nominate Ryota Mibu to the Aodh core team. he has been
an active participant in Aodh and leads the Event alarms work
done there. he also brings good insight related to NFV use case.

patches:
https://review.openstack.org/#/q/owner:%22Ryota+MIBU%22+project:openstack/aodh,n,z

reviews:

get_samples uses concurrent querying

Instead of sequentially querying for
measurements of a metric with different
dimensions, this patch queries them
at same time using mult-tasking.

Change-Id: Ief0d588ed1cc6d6ed0d1a198e888d545c32c188c

Add override endpoint

The endpoint defined in env 'OS_DNS_ENDPOINT' overrides the one
defined in service catalog.

commit_message:
Use clouds.yaml from devstack for functional tests

devstack produces a file called clouds.yaml already with credentials in
it. Rather than producing our own config file to run functional tests,
just consume the clouds.yaml file that's already there.

Closes-Bug: #1507386
Change-Id: Ie15b5da2e61f5b35e3bdeb75f0ba21c58ddfca76

We decided to remove the GPFS driver before Liberty-RC1 because there was no working CI system, but the CI system has since been setup and is working, so we have reverted the removal patch in master.

Since the removal propagated to the stable/liberty branch as well we need to revert the removal here too.

commit_message:
Set ip_nonlocal_bind in namespace if it exists

Somewhere in the 3.19 kernel timeframe ip_nonlocal_bind was
changed to be a per-namespace attribute. To be backwards
compatible we need to try that first, then fall-back to
setting the one in the root namespace if it fails.

Closes-Bug: #1507078
Change-Id: I018e800bc8d4e85d067aaae865c9b04bf030c980

commit_message:
ovs: remove several unneeded object attributes from setup_rpc()

It's currently not clear what the interactions and interdependencies
between existing attributes set inside setup_rpc() and other code are.
This complicates its perception. So reduce the complexity a bit by using
local variables instead of object attributes where applies; and moving
agent_id calculation out of setup_rpc() since it's not related to AMQP.

Change-Id: I6ad156a7dd686ab2a2349704a34385db1ee9681c

commit_message:
Fix iptables comments for bare jump rules

This fixes the order of arguments in iptables rules that
are bare jumps (e.g. '-j other-chain').

The previous code was only catching jump rules that appeared
after a chain definition.

Closes-Bug: #1502932
Change-Id: I490792eb08c67a32f9b286d933a776fb76840b6b
(cherry picked from commit 2a4b5f938d038bd73a70f1fc86cc71e819e288b0)

commit_message:
Add heat support

A lovely human upstream in ansible submitted a heat module - which means
that it needs to be rewritten to use shade - which means we need heat
support in shade. Add it.

Change-Id: Idb0fe452698d74180a0ae96963c3d8cbca4d47e5

commit_message:
Update gerrit javamelody plugin builds

Build javamelody against gerrit 2.11 branch in preparation for gerrit
upgrade. Remove 2.9 and 2.10 builds because those were never deployed
to our production gerrit.

Change-Id: I50feaa6cde37a651f35e5d864ae729c17fc3d100
depends-on: I9cd68e4e1467aa820ca8c5b125278332a2f2e216

commit_message:
Update instructions to deploy with Ceph

Users don't need to edit the storage-environment.yaml file and we
also don't use Tuskar by default anymore.

Change-Id: Id44d8862ca20524460fb70127559e366d1d3a438

[{'created': '2015-10-19 15:20:39.000000000', 'message': 'Fix a race calling blocking MessageHandlingServer.start()

This fixes a race due to the quirkiness of the blocking executor. The
blocking executor does not create a separate thread, but is instead
explicitly executed in the calling thread. Other threads will,
however, continue to interact with it.

In the non-blocking case, the executor will have done certain
initialisation in start() before starting a worker thread and
returning control to the caller. That is, the caller can be sure that
this initialisation has occurred when control is returned. However, in
the blocking case, control is never returned. We currently work round
this by setting self._running to True before executing executor.start,
and by not doing any locking whatsoever in MessageHandlingServer.
However, this current means there is a race whereby executor.stop()
can run before executor.start(). This is fragile and extremely
difficult to reason about robustly, if not currently broken.

The solution is to split the initialisation from the execution in the
blocking case. executor.start() is no longer a blocking operation for
the blocking executor. As for the non-blocking case, executor.start()
returns as soon as initialisation is complete, indicating that it is
safe to subsequently call stop(). Actual execution is done explicitly
via the new execute() method, which blocks.

Change-Id: I0d332f74c06c22b44179319432153e15b69f2f45

commit_message:
Fix a race calling blocking MessageHandlingServer.start()

This fixes a race due to the quirkiness of the blocking executor. The
blocking executor does not create a separate thread, but is instead
explicitly executed in the calling thread. Other threads will,
however, continue to interact with it.

In the non-blocking case, the executor will have done certain
initialisation in start() before starting a worker thread and
returning control to the caller. That is, the caller can be sure that
this initialisation has occurred when control is returned. However, in
the blocking case, control is never returned. We currently work round
this by setting self._running to True before executing executor.start,
and by not doing any locking whatsoever in MessageHandlingServer.
However, this current means there is a race whereby executor.stop()
can run before executor.start(). This is fragile and extremely
difficult to reason about robustly, if not currently broken.

The solution is to split the initialisation from the execution in the
blocking case. executor.start() is no longer a blocking operation for
the blocking executor. As for the non-blocking case, executor.start()
returns as soon as initialisation is complete, indicating that it is
safe to subsequently call stop(). Actual execution is done explicitly
via the new execute() method, which blocks.

In doing this, we also make FakeBlockingThread a more complete
implementation of threading.Thread. This fixes a related issue in
that, previously, calling server.wait() on a blocking executor from
another thread would not wait for the completion of the executor. This
has a knock-on effect in test_server's ServerSetupMixin. This mixin
created an endpoint with a stop method which called server.stop().
However, as this is executed by the executor, and also joins the
executor thread, which is now blocking, this results in a deadlock. I
am satisfied that, in general, this is not a sane thing to do.
However, it is useful for these tests. We fix the tests by making the
stop method non-blocking, and do the actual stop and wait calls from
the main thread.

Change-Id: I0d332f74c06c22b44179319432153e15b69f2f45

commit_message:
Fix assumptions in test_server_wait_method

test_server_wait_method was calling server.wait without having
previously called server.start and server.stop. This happened to work
because it also injected server._executor_obj. This is problematic,
though, as it assumes internal details of the server and does not
represent the calling contract of server.wait, which is that it must
follow server.stop (which must itself also follow server.start).

This change makes the necessary changes to call server.wait in the
correct sequence.

Change-Id: I205683ac6e0f2d64606bb06d08d3d1419f7645f4

commit_message:
Rename MessageHandlingServer._executor for readability

MessageHandlingServer has both MessageHandlingServer.executor, which
is the name of an executor type, and MessageHandlingServer._executor,
which is an instance of that type. Ideally we would rename
MessageHandlingServer.executor, but as this is referenced from outside
the class we change _executor instead to _executor_obj.

Change-Id: Id69ba7a0729cc66d266327dac2fd4eab50f2814c

commit_message:
Change section name for AMQP qpid parameters

According to docs for liberty and kilo [1,2] should be
section 'oslo_messaging_qpid' instead of 'DEFAULT'.

[1] http://docs.openstack.org/liberty/config-reference/content/configuring-rpc.html
[2] http://docs.openstack.org/kilo/config-reference/content/configuring-rpc.html

Change-Id: I2532141fc1659e6e2123250f69a1834297df5f36

commit_message:
Fix test_two_pools_three_listener to not restart servers

test_two_pools_three_listener currently starts, stops, and
subsequently restarts servers while testing pools. This is problematic
if we don't want to support restarting a server after it has been
stopped.

This change discards a server after it has been stopped, and creates a
new one when it is required again.

Change-Id: I88d50d75a6965bde6f2a6832620383120ab8f09e

commit_message:
Use local.conf instead of localrc

  Use actual local.conf file name and format
  instead of deprecated localrc in devstack related
  deployment engines.

  Closes-bug: #1457194

commit_message:
Ambari mirror image type

If user wants to create Ambari cluster without internet access,
he will need to have mirror with all required HDP stack packages,
HDP Utils packages, and probably some other base packages, which
also will be used during cluster creation (as requirements for HDP
stack packages or HDP UTILS packages).

So, this change introduce new image type ambari-mirror, which
will consist of 3 repos: hdp, hdp-utils, and extra repo.
This image type will support only centos and centos7, because sahara
support only these distros. This image type will collect all needed stuff, 
so instances of cluster will be able to install packages from this local
repositories.

Change-Id: Ib0d4fc61c154df4c19f9dbd6c843a6d4d5d23af3

commit_message:
Change section name for AMQP qpid parameters

According to docs for liberty and kilo [1,2] should be
section 'oslo_messaging_qpid' instead of 'DEFAULT'.

[1] http://docs.openstack.org/liberty/config-reference/content/configuring-rpc.html
[2] http://docs.openstack.org/kilo/config-reference/content/configuring-rpc.html

Change-Id: I0dbdda51fc20cec95cbcf8769034692a5ffb92d6

> 1. Does vif_driver belong in libvirt.pp or neutron.pp?

It's already in neutron.pp, let's keep it for backward compatibility. I don't see why we would change it now.

> 2. class nova::compute::neutron is not included anywhere. Is it not used by default or is the class deprecated?

You need to include it yourself in your composition layer. This class IS NOT deprecated at all.

> 3. Lastly, if neutron.pp is the right place, does it make sense to have $force_snat_range default value to be undef? Since, we want libvirt_vif_driver to be set independently of force_snat_range value.

commit_message:
Make libvirt_vif_driver configurable

This change exposes libvirt_vif_driver configuration parameter.
It will allow a user to set this value, if required. Else the
default value of undefined will be used and the parameter will
not be added to the config file, as it is done today.

libvirt_vif_driver value is used to configure VIFs by providing
driver choices based on the network type.

Added spec tests for libvirt_vif_driver

Change-Id: I539126344df71d1f6f8af58223c1fa51e59dccba

commit_message:
Remove unused code from cinderclient.utils module

_format_servers_list_networks method is not used anywhere.
It's safe to delete it.

We'ge got the same cinderclient.openstack.common.apiclient.HookableMixin
class so we don't need to duplicate it in the utils

Change-Id: Ifa7f5c1d00c1673811af48575460e6563d2d3180

commit_message:
Update release notes for 1.3.1 and 1.4.0 releases

We've had a couple releases of the client but missed updating
the docs with any release note information. Added summary of
changes for each release.

Closes-Bug: #1503705

commit_message:
Add doc8 job to run doc8 testing

Allow doc8 testing which can catch common formatting and syntax errors
present in rst files. Typically the tox -edocs command is used to
include doc8 testing but the job template for 'docs' runs build_sphinx
directly. If you want to include this job in your project you will need
to add a new tox env for doc8.

Change-Id: I6d42cb2092cbaed0cc2ed83f23b7f9ce0b52356f

commit_message:
Label on chart tooltip changed

Old tooltip format {label}: {value}, {percentage}% confuses
when you see, for instance: kvm: 441, 84%. This can be
recognized as 441,84%

Change-Id: I4ccffc2d08a4d35fa2fc257da014403ff1f09480
Closes-Bug: #1507929

Just a note to say I've looked at it, am not opposed, looking forward to the revised version per discussion in #openstack-glance"}, {'account_id': 5314, 'date': '2015-08-12 04:21:39.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 4:

I'd like you to say some more about how you see this hanging together.  Is it something like this?

Glance admin:
POST /v2/tasks
{ "type": "trigger", "input": { "event": "image.activate", "task": "convert" }}
This creates task-1.  Nothing happens beyond triger-task creation at this point.

Glance end-user
POST /v2/tasks
{ "type": "import", "input": { "import-from": <URL> }}
This creates task-2, which is executed the normal way and results in image-1 being created in Glance and going active.
 As part of the image activation (?) the task_trigger table is scanned and task-1 is located.

(I'm not clear what happens here, just guessing based on the spec)

POST /v2/tasks
{ "type": "convert", "input": { "image": "image-1", <more stuff here> }}
This creates task-3, which would be executed the normal way.

Questions:
- if there needs to be "<more stuff here>" in task-3, how does that get specified?  Does the trigger task provide a way to refer to properties of the image that's activated so that they can be used when the executable task is created?
- who's running task-3? the glance admin, or the end-user who owns the image?
- the above gives you a trigger-task that will create a new convert task for every image that's created.  Is that the right idea, or would the trigger-task only apply to some images? If so, how are these images specified?
- maybe I'm being misled by my own example, but the above looks like it would be better handled by adding a conversion step to the input task instead of by a trigger-task.'}, {'account_id': 2109, 'date': '2015-08-12 17:39:38.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 4: Code-Review+1

As a deployer of OpenStack for public cloud, this automatic task triggering is definitely a feature that I'd like to see supported, and the described implementation in the spec is reasonable and flexible, without being overcomplicated. I wholeheartedly support this spec, and look forward to being able to leverage this functionality to automatically convert uploaded customer images to RAW format for Ceph RBD."}, {'account_id': 6159, 'date': '2015-08-14 08:42:22.000000000', 'content': 'Uploaded patch set 5.'}, {'account_id': 3, 'date': '2015-08-14 08:48:02.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 5: Verified-1

Build failed (check pipeline).  For information on how to proceed, see http://docs.openstack.org/infra/manual/developers.html#automated-testing

- gate-glance-specs-docs http://logs.openstack.org/88/188388/5/check/gate-glance-specs-docs/b95166d/ : FAILURE in 1m 54s
- gate-glance-specs-python27 http://logs.openstack.org/88/188388/5/check/gate-glance-specs-python27/61cc459/ : SUCCESS in 2m 12s'}, {'account_id': 6159, 'date': '2015-08-14 08:49:13.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 5:

Brian, thanks a lot for the review:

Your understanding is not very far from what is being proposed, except for the semantics of the API calls. I've uploaded a new version containing 2 examples that will hopefully help clearing this up. To answer your questions:

1) Yes, the trigger task will provide the required information, this means that one can't create a trigger task for tasks that require dynamic input.

2) It really depends on the policies/permissions of that Glance instance. Trigger tasks are not meant to be created by final users. Therefore, we'll add a policy to prevent that. However, normal tasks execution could, as it is today, be triggered by the final user unless the admin disables it.

3) The trigger task will create a new task every time action 'X' happens, yes. That's the idea.

4) What you're probably missing is that these tasks are meant to be executed not just during `import` but also other normal Glance actions - image creation, deletion, upload, for example.


Hope the above helps clearing things out a bit, let me know if you've more questions."}, {'account_id': 6159, 'date': '2015-08-14 08:50:36.000000000', 'content': 'Uploaded patch set 6.'}, {'account_id': 3, 'date': '2015-08-14 08:56:09.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 6: Verified+1

commit_message:
Refactor stack tests.

Moving the stack CRUD related tests that don't need engine service, from
test_engine_service to test_stack. These tests belong to stack tests
rather than engine service tests.

[{'created': '2015-10-16 16:18:28.000000000', 'message': 'Correct conditionals and dnsmasq reload for deploy

The conditionals in the deployment role were incorrect if the
inventory data source was set to ironic where the interpretted
reply from the API could include an empty instance_info dictonary.

Changed the conditionals to handle the condition where the
dictonary may be empty.

Additionally changed the dnsmasq handling to directly HUP the
dnsmasq process as the service init file, if present, may not
support reloaded state as Ansible passes it directly through.

Change-Id: Id84b8869ef5fc9deb1eee8cc304ee00713a3016a
'}]
commit_message:
Correct conditionals and dnsmasq reload for deploy

The conditionals in the deployment role were incorrect if the
inventory data source was set to ironic where the interpretted
reply from the API could include an empty instance_info dictonary.

Changed the conditionals to handle the condition where the
dictonary may be empty.

Additionally changed the dnsmasq handling to directly HUP the
dnsmasq process as the service init file, if present, may not
support reloaded state as Ansible passes it directly through.

Change-Id: Id84b8869ef5fc9deb1eee8cc304ee00713a3016a

commit_message:
Improve message for publish package conflict

When user publish a package conflict with another public package with same FQN,
API server will throw webob.exc.HTTPConflict. So catch the exception on
dashboard and give back a specific reason to user.

Change-Id: I3cd7ea24c6645487e6c7155a1f530c64f31bd332
Closes-Bug: #1475079
Co-authored-by: zhu.rong <zhu.rong@99cloud.net>

commit_message:
use full path to call the ip command

ip command is in /sbin directory. This directory is not of a standard
user default path. By using the full path we make sure we are still able
to execute ip even if the user $PATH is unchanged.

Change-Id: Ife29b38d7998d949ffae3ce09ec256d7fb21ce5a

commit_message:
Update rspec tests for keystone

https://review.openstack.org/#/c/228744/ has been merged, we need to
drop the 'tenant' parameter to Keystone_user resource.

Change-Id: Ifa3b13eef94d46c4008f7cb0707169f581ddf153

revisions:
[{'created': '2015-10-20 16:27:03.000000000', 'message': 'Use DIB_EPEL_MIRROR when finding the epel-release package

download.fedoraproject.org uses dns round robin and occasionally
hits a bad server. Using DIB_EPEL_MIRROR when finding the
epel-release package will allow us to avoid it e.g. in ci.

Change-Id: I756223b3e669532476663c05e79c238449b8a0db
'}]
commit_message:
Use DIB_EPEL_MIRROR when finding the epel-release package

download.fedoraproject.org uses dns round robin and occasionally
hits a bad server. Using DIB_EPEL_MIRROR when finding the
epel-release package will allow us to avoid it e.g. in ci.

Change-Id: I756223b3e669532476663c05e79c238449b8a0db

commit_message:
Remove unused sphinx Makefile

The appropriate way to build sphinx docs in OpenStack is:

  tox -evenv -- python setup.py build_sphinx

commit_message:
Update docs to recommend KSA instead of KSC

For the session workflow (which is really the only workflow a dev should
use), session objects should now come from keystoneauth1 instead of
python-keystoneclient.

Change-Id: Icb5f20ce3dc09ff7790b27d07f7f0cb3b83e1e7e

commit_message:
Correct usage of API_MAX_VERSION and DEFAULT_OS_COMPUTE_API_VERSION

Commit d045019f0f2d28f26730b3617f7d7b993506b6e8 use the variables
API_MAX_VERSION and DEFAULT_OS_COMPUTE_API_VERSION with wrong way.

API_MAX_VERSION means the max version of client supported. This
variable only be changed when client support the new version. And
it's must bumped sequentially.

DEFAULT_OS_COMPUTE_API_VERSION is default value of option
'--os-compute-api-version', this value decided the default behaviour
of nova client. The nova client CLI behaviour should be that client
negotiate with server side to find out most recent version betweeyn
client and server. So the value should be '2.latest'. And it won't
be changed except we decided to change the default behaviour of nova
client CLI.

Change-Id: Iba9bfa136245bd2899c427ac0c231a30c00bd7f3
Closes-Bug: #1508244

commit_message:
Separate uploading packages for patching

- RPM packages are uploaded after Fuel admin node bootstrapped,
  as previous;
- DEB packages are uploaded after Fuel admin node deployed and
  'auxiliary' repository initialized.

Change-Id: I5c423529e175ef6ddfc9ac5f5e2359e1e0b6d32f
Closes-Bug:#1502242
(cherry picked from commit a8c4492e12ce58badffa5e90caab6672c6c0e732)

commit_message:
Remove IBM SDN-VE left-overs

The project has been removed in I8def7fc2e92f967785b9ab05f8496de641e8f866
and it's been retired from stackforge [1]. So it's safe to remove it from
the list with the remaining bits.

commit_message:
Port test_cache_manage to Python 3

* Decode HTTP body from UTF-8 to get Unicode on Python 3. The test
  still works on Python 2.
* tox.ini: add test_cache_manage to Python 3.4.

Change-Id: I637732cb06b7ae30853b35d2a83aa85f643fd43b

commit_message:
Remove os-loganalyze from PROJECTS

os-loganalyze was added to PROJECTS so that it could be used in
devstack. We don't currently run any jobs that use os-loganalyze with
d-g so we don't actually need this. Any new jobs that do want to use it
can be explicit about requiring it in their PROJECTS list.

Change-Id: I4db4fe1511c32fa16d47cda0a11bf44815646ede

Do not check doc folder in pep8 check

This patch includes an exclusion of the doc directory from the pep8
check as the documentation conf.py requires a lengthy line.

commit_message:
drop v1 client

we dropped v1 back in Juno. as icehouse is EOL and the client
follows stable/branches, v1 is completely inaccessible and can be
removed

Co-Authored-By: ZhiQiang Fan <aji.zqfan@gmail.com>
Closes-Bug: #1389331

https://review.openstack.org/#/c/228744/ has been merged, we need to
drop the 'tenant' parameter to Keystone_user resource.

commit_message:
Abstract out the name of the name key

Heat and Cinder each have different key names for their "name" concept.
Rather than keeping a list of them, make an argument so we can override
it in the instances we need to.

Change-Id: I6ba0b69129c74e976ea6762728a940b4670f3873

commit_message:
Add heatclient support

In support of https://github.com/ansible/ansible-modules-core/pull/2036
add at least a heat client constructor.

Also, check it out - heatclient doesn't support Session auth. Until it
does, we're not going to support advanced things like overriding SSL
args.

Change-Id: I488fde4abe5abc1c58515cf77d08644b49eb5ba6

Per brief conversation with Tim, I like this change.  metrics.metrics.metrics is rough looking but I can't think of better names for either the file or the singleton."}, {'account_id': 12000, 'date': '2015-10-19 15:17:55.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 2: Code-Review-1

(5 comments)

I like the direction of this change, but I think using a module singleton is not the best approach.

A quick look at the files affected seem to indicate to me that the only object that doesn't have access to the Manager is the Node Visitor. 

In my opinion the Node Visitor class is an implementation detail so we could instantiate it with another parameter, the instance of Metrics on the manager. This would share the instance appropriately and have the same benefit of sharing a single object for aggregating metrics. (BanditManager is the only thing I can see that instantiates a Node Visitor so I think we should be safe.)

This also means that we can avoid having module level functions to do a lot of this for us.

That said, I still think properties on the Metrics class will make accessing data easier.

If you want to stick with a module singleton, I think we should add module level functions to make things simpler to read then."}, {'account_id': 11716, 'date': '2015-10-21 13:06:39.000000000', 'content': 'Uploaded patch set 3.'}, {'account_id': 11716, 'date': '2015-10-21 13:07:49.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 3:

commit_message:
Collecting metrics code in one place

The metrics gathering code was spread out throught the code base
(manager, node_visitor, reporters). This gathers as much as we
can into a single new class. Functionality is unchanged, coverage
is 100%

It also tweeks the interface to the node visitor. Process() now
takes a list of lines, rather than the file object. It would only
use this file object to read lines, this is now done in the
manager. Most metrics code is now called by the manager, the
exception being note_nosec() as this has to be called by the
node_visitor still.

Change-Id: Ibfae3c2b229fda999b998730d4c9301f4a7ccc45

commit_message:
Stop corosync in upgrade seed during control plane switch

Stop corosync cluster before switching to upgraded control plane.
Start corosync cluster once switch is complete.
Don't stop cluster if there is only one controller in seed environment.

Closes-bug: 1506398
Change-Id: Ie5684155899675ce1c35636d9e892d399e41b790
